<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Must Own Up Kargil Mistake for Talks: India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee said on Tuesday that talks with Pakistan were
possible only after Islamabad owned up its mistake of foisting the
Kargil war on India and desisted from sponsoring cross-border
terrorism, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
However, Vajpayee also noted that India realized the importance
of holding talks with Pakistan for normalization of relations
between the two countries, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a public meeting in West India's Gujarat State,
Vajpayee criticized Pakistan as a "theocratic state" indulging in
anti-India and anti-Hindu propaganda in order to divert the
attention of its people from its internal problems, the PTI
reported.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan had betrayed India's trust and stabbed it in the back
by waging the Kargil war of last summer, Vajpayee said, obviously
referring to his peace-seeking bus journey to Lahore in February
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
