<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Refutes Rumors with Regard to DPRK-Germany Contact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) on Monday refuted rumors spread by some "
foreign forces" that Germany had put pressure on the DPRK when the
foreign ministers of the two countries made contact recently in
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question by the Korean Central News Agency (KCNA),
a DPRK Foreign Ministry spokesman said that on April 5 the DPRK
foreign minister met his German counterpart during his stopover in
Berlin en route to Colombia to participate in the meeting of
foreign ministers of non-aligned countries.
</P>
<P>
During the contact, the DPRK side informed the German side of
the recent situation in the DPRK, its proposals for national
reunification and independent foreign policy and both sides
exchanged views on matters of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister of the DPRK clarified the country's
principled stand on a series of issues raised at the contact, and
the two sides reached a consensus that it is in bilateral interest
to continue discussions on issues of mutual concern in the future.
</P>
<P>
But some forces let media under their control spread
misinformation about the contact. They asserted that the German
side put sort of "pressure" on the DPRK, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Friendly relations are established and developed between states
not by any "request" or "pressure" from someone under any
circumstances but by each other's independent decision and
judgment on the principle of sovereignty, mutual respect and
equality, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK government will as ever establish and develop friendly
and cooperative relations with all the countries which respect its
sovereignty and are friendly to it on the basis of the fundamental
idea of independence, peace and friendship, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
