<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Calls for Efforts to Protect Collective South Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Cuban Foreign Minister Felipe
Perez Roque Tuesday called for closer cooperation among developing
countries to collectively protect the interests of the peoples in
the South against the current unjust international economic system.
</P>
<P>
Delivering his welcoming statement at the opening session of
the meeting of foreign ministers here, the foreign minister said,
"The time has come. Our peoples have run out of patience. For
decades they have suffered broken promises, and are today living
in an economic and social situation that is increasingly serious."
</P>
<P>
"It is more essential and urgent than ever before, that the
Group of 77 adopts a common strategy to defend our interests," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The South Summit was launched in the Caribbean island country
after the failure of the World Conference of the World Trade
Organization in Seattle, the United States, and with just a few
months before the Convocation of the Millennium Summit in
September at the United Nations Headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
"Now is the time to forge a common stance for our 133 countries
to demand a more just world, based on solidarity," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The 1.3 billion people on the Planet, who are struggling today
to survive in circumstances which are classified as 'critical
poverty', have good reason to hope that their children will not
have to put up with this tragedy at their lives," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The 900 million starving people on the Planet have every right
to hope that the wonderful scientific and technological advances,
and the increase in world trade will mean that they at least have
a decent plate of food every day," he continued.
</P>
<P>
"The parents of the 12 million children who will die this year
from illness that are completely preventable, have every right to
hope that this South Summit will be devoted to defending the most
important human right: the right to life," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have the right to dream of a future for our children that
is better than the lives we have lived," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The globalization of the world economy cannot carry on causing
underdevelopment, poverty and exclusion for the majority, and
wasteful and unnecessary luxury for a privileged minority," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials began a working meeting on Monday morning to
hammer out the two draft documents to be adopted at the end of the
Summit on April 14. Foreign ministers will consider the drafts and
then submit them for the approval of heads of state and government
when they begin to meet for three days on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Although the G-77 membership grew to 133 countries over the
past decades, the original name of the body, set up by 77
developing countries in June 1964 in Geneva, was retained due to
its historic significance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
