<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Community Urged to Aid Drought-Hit Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Representatives in
Ethiopia Tuesday urged the international community to step up food
aid to drought- affected people in the Horn of Africa country.
</P>
<P>
The relief food extended so far by the international community
is not adequate, said representatives from the World Food Program
(WFP), the World Health Organization (WHO), The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF), the United Nations Development Program
(UNDP) and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The world community should stretch out a continuous food
assistance to stem the food crisis in Ethiopia, they said.
</P>
<P>
"We have too little to many people right now (in Ethiopia),"
said WFP country representative Judith Louis, who stressed that
the country needs immediate pledges from the donor community.
</P>
<P>
She said the relief food from donors should reach in Ethiopia
by the end of next June.
</P>
<P>
WHO country representative Michel Janclos said that although
WHO has distributed food among the drought-affected people, the
supplies are not sufficient compared with the gravity of the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a representative from UNICEF said the U.N. body has
appealed for 7.7 million U.S. dollars to provide clean water as
well as health and emergency education services to people hit by
drought.
</P>
<P>
However, so far only 500,000 U.S. dollars has been received,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
Large part of Ethiopia has been reportedly suffering from
drought since late last year with more than eight million people
facing starvation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
