<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Invites More Foreign Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia's Trade Center
announced on Wednesday that a number of invitations will be sent to
potential foreign investors to attract investments needed for Saudi
projects.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the office of Saudi Prince Tala Ibn Abdul-Aziz,
chairman of the trade center, said the center had asked a Saudi
bank to deliver the invitations to investors who are willing to
invest in the Gulf kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came just two days after Saudi cabinet endorsed
a new foreign investment law on Monday, which encourages foreign
investments by allowing 100 percent ownership rights and reducing
corporate tax for foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners had been limited to 49 percent stakes in joint
ventures and barred from owning property in the kingdom where about
a quarter of 20 million people are expatriates.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law, corporate taxes imposed on firms with high
profits of over 100,000 Saudi riyals (26,660 U.S. dollars) are
likely to be reduced to 30 percent from 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
The new legislation also changed the old arrangement stipulating
that all foreigner workers in the kingdom must have Saudi sponsors,
a move which received widespread applause from the expatriates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Calls for Inter-Arab Parliamentary Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti National Assembly
Speaker Jasim Al-Kharafi on Wednesday called for cooperation among
parliaments of Arab countries, particularly between Kuwait and
Yemen, in order to settle differences among the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming his visiting Yemeni counterpart Sheikh Abdullah Al-
Ahmar, Al-Kharafi said the "Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990 was
the main reason for the rupture of the Arab fold."
</P>
<P>
The 1991 Gulf war triggered by Iraq's invasion and occupation of
Kuwait led to a nine-year freeze of ties between Kuwait and Yemen
since Sanaa showed sympathy with Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The two countries restored full relations in May last year, when
Yemen reopened its embassy in Kuwait after nine years of closure.
</P>
<P>
Al-Kharafi said that "cutting ties between the two countries
reflected badly on bilateral relations as well as on the Arab and
Islamic relations."
</P>
<P>
But the Kuwaiti parliament leader expressed hope that both
countries will join hands at all levels because there "is no choice
but cooperation."
</P>
<P>
For his part, the Yemeni speaker, who arrived in Kuwait on
Monday on a four-day visit, also voiced hope that his visit, the
first of its kind in almost 10 years, "would foster ties to secure
the interests of both states."
</P>
<P>
Ahmar also hoped this visit would end with fruitful results on
the way of cooperation and joint action between the two
parliaments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Explosions Shock Northeastern Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Two explosions shocked Iran's
northeastern city of Mashhad on Wednesday, but caused no
casualties, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The explosions occurred at about 4 p.m. and 4:30 p.m. local time
(1130 GMT and 1200 GMT) in two places in Mashhad, Khorassan
province, according to Hussein Zare, deputy governor general for
political and security affairs in the province.
</P>
<P>
He said the first explosion occurred in the Taleqani street near
the Homa hotel, which was apparently caused by a bomb planted in a
dustbin.
</P>
<P>
The other explosion took place in the lane Khamenei near the
holy shrine of Imam Reza. No one was hurt and only some windows
were shattered, he added.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been in a political tension since the sixth
parliamentary elections in February, in which reformers supporting
President Mohammad Khatami won a landslide victory over their
conservative rivals.
</P>
<P>
The conservative Guardians Council, supervisor of the elections,
recently cancelled the election results in some constituencies,
which has stirred up a series of protests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
