<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kofi Annan Proposes to Create Health Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan recommended Wednesday the creation of a world health
network through the Internet to provide a wide range of
information on the latest scientific knowledge to the developing
world's hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Annan spoke at the opening session of the South Summit before
heads of state, ministers and ambassadors of the member countries
from the Group of 77 (G-77).
</P>
<P>
He explained that his report at the Millennium Summit includes
two initiatives destined at putting information technology at the
service of Third World countries' populations.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the creation of an Internet health network, he said
that there will be over 10,000 on-line sites to serve hospitals,
clinics and medical installations in every developing country.
</P>
<P>
It will be possible to have access to up-to-date instantaneous
medical information adapted to the needs of these medical centers,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The second initiative presented by the U.N. secretary-general
includes the formation of voluntary corps specialized in advanced
technology, which will train professionals in developing countries
in the use of information technology.
</P>
<P>
Both initiatives, said Annan, will be carried out through
alliances between the United Nations, the private sector,
philanthropic foundations and every institution aimed at serving
people in the North as well as in the South. 
</P>
</TEXT>
