<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-77 Pays Homage to Julius Nyerere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Group of 77 (G-77) paid homage
Wednesday here to one of the historical pillars in South-South
cooperation, the late Tanzanian President Julius Nyerere.
</P>
<P>
The G-77 president, Nigerian leader Olusegun Obasanjo, asked
the South Summit assistants for a minute of silence to the memory
of the Third World African leader, who passed away last year.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo referred to Nyerere as an eminent world leader and as
an outstanding founding figure in Africa who gave invaluable
services for the establishment of South-South cooperation and
contributed to the principles that serve as a base to the South
Summit which started Wednesday in Havana.
</P>
<P>
About contacts among developing countries, the G-77 leader
regretted that many of the numerous agreements have been moved out
of the United Nations reach because "we will enter the new
millennium with many of our expectations affected by the
globalizing wave."
</P>
<P>
Among the negative effects of this situation, he talked about
poverty in developing countries, and the fall in every human
development indicator. A new strategy to cope with this problems
is needed, he added.
</P>
<P>
Developed countries, he said, still are the great beneficiaries
of this situation, while most of the developing countries are
lacking opportunities such as those developed countries can count
on.
</P>
<P>
Globalization has not propitiated economic recovery, higher
growth and more opportunities for the eradication of misery in the
developing world, Obasanjo added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
