<HEADLINE> Queen Presents N.Irish Police Heroism Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 12 (Xinhua -- Queen Elizabeth flew into Northern
Ireland on Wednesday and presented its battle-scarred police force
with the George Cross, Britain's highest civilian gallantry award.
</P>
<P>
Under tight security after recent attacks by republican
renegades, she lauded the record of the Royal Ulster Constabulary
(RUC) record during 30 years of strife.
</P>
<P>
"This award is an exceptional recognition of the outstanding
contribution made by the RUC to peace in Northern Ireland," she
told hundreds of police officers and families, including widows,at
Hillsborough Castle.
</P>
<P>
Paying tribute to the 302 officers who died and the thousands
who were wounded, she said it was "a singular acknowledgment of
the gallantry and courage shown, and on all too many occasions,
the ultimate sacrifice paid, by the members of the constabulary...
"
</P>
<P>
Reforms to the largely Protestant force, especially plans to
drop the "royal" tag in a new name, have riled pro-British
Protestant unionists, who say the changes insult the force's
casualties in sectarian violence that took 3,600 lives.
</P>
<P>
Widespread changes to Northern Ireland's police service will go
ahead, Tony Blair confirmed on the day the force was awarded the
George Cross.
</P>
<P>
Paying tribute to the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the prime
minister nevertheless insisted changes to make it more acceptable
to the whole community, were vital.
</P>
<P>
The Queen presented Britain's highest civilian award for
gallantry, speaking of the "exceptional recognition of the
outstanding contribution made by the RUC to peace in Northern
Ireland".
</P>
<P>
But many former, serving and disabled RUC officers, have said
that if the government changes the force's name to the Police
Service for Northern Ireland it would be a crushing blow.
</P>
<P>
In the House of Commons, Tony Blair said: "Many officers died
during that period of time, many others suffered loss of limb.
</P>
<P>
"Their families have often lived in the most appalling
circumstances of fear and terror and I am delighted and honored to
pay my tribute to the RUC for all the work that they've done,"
Blair said.
</P>
<P>
Some unionist politicians have expressed concern that the award
of the George Cross at this time was an attempt to damp down anger
about the proposed changes.
</P>
<P>
Republicans have also condemned the award of the medal. Sinn
Fein's Bairbre de Brun described it as "offensive" to members of
the nationalist community killed and injured by the "discredited
force".
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein staged a protest in Londonderry against the ceremony
as it was taking place and a victims' group, Relatives for Justice,
held a black flag vigil at Belfast City Hall to protest against
the award.
</P>
<P>
But Ulster Unionist Leader David Trimble said the award
recognized the "service and sacrifice of the RUC" in the way the
Patten report did not.
</P>
<P>
The UUP, the largest political party in Northern Ireland,
recently decided to link retaining the RUC's name with political
progress.
</P>
<P>
The RUC was awarded the George Cross in tribute to the
sacrifice and service of its members and to recognize the force's
bravery during more than 30 years of paramilitary violence in the
province.
</P>
<P>
Three officers received the medal on behalf of the force at a
ceremony at Hillsborough Castle in County Down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
