<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Objects to Resuming Turtle Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The World Wildlife Foundation
announced Wednesday in a news release that it completely objected
to Cuba's proposal to reopen the international trade in Hawksbill
turtle.
</P>
<P>
"We shouldn't reopen the trade because controls in the main
importing country, Japan, are inadequate, the status of the turtle
populations in the Caribbean is unclear, and regional management
is patchy," said Elizabeth Kemf, WWF Species Information Manager,
in her newly published report.
</P>
<P>
Despite decades of conservation efforts, six of the world's
seven species of marine turtle are still in danger of extinction,
Kemf said in the report entitled "Wanted Alive! Marine Turtles in
the Wild".
</P>
<P>
"Local extinctions of marine turtles have occurred in all ocean
basins, and no population, not even those that are stable as a
result of long term conservation and management, is completely
safe," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Hawksbills, like other marine turtles, are facing ever-growing
numbers of threats," she said in the report.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, though trade in turtles is banned
under CITES, they are still hunted and sold openly as tourist
curios in Vietnam, Cambodia, Mexico and parts of the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Up to 300,000 turtles are killed each year as "bycatch" in
trawling nets or shrimp nets, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that tourism is also a major threat to turtles because
the construction of seawalls, hotels and other facilities have
destroyed large areas of turtle nesting beaches around the world.
</P>
<P>
Cuba and Dominica have proposed that the ongoing Convention on
the Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES)
held in Nairobi should resume the international trade in Hawksbill
turtle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Raise Minimum Wage for Public Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has set up
a 19- member committee to review salaries and allowances for its
600,000 strong public sector workers in an effort to narrow the
gap with the private sector, a senior government official said in
a statement published here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The committee, headed by chief economic adviser to the
president Philip Asiodu, would help "narrow the gap between wages
in the public and private sectors," in the interest of the
management of the economy, said Ufot Ekaette, secretary to the
Nigerian government.
</P>
<P>
"The government considers that there is now an urgent need to
initiate the process of raising the level of wages and associated
allowances payable to workers in the public sector," he said.
</P>
<P>
Already the government has provided 8.6 billion naira (one U.S.
dollar equals 100 naira at present) in this year's budget in
anticipation of the wage increase. The step would enhance the
success of the government's campaign against corruption, Ekaette
said.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which includes eight representatives of the
government and six representatives of the Nigeria Labor Congress,
also includes representatives of the employers association, the
Chamber of Commerce and farmers.
</P>
<P>
Public sector wages were increased early last year when the
former military leader Abdulsalami Abubakar raised the minimum
wage from 1,200 naira to 3,500 monthly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
