<HEADLINE> Condition of Comatose Iranian Reformer Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A prominent Iranian reformer, who
was injured in a car accident Wednesday morning, is now in a coma
and breathes through a respirator, but his condition is said to be
improving.
</P>
<P>
Rajabali Mazroui, head of Iran's Association of Journalists, was
hospitalized in the intensive care unit of Tehran's Day hospital,
and a surgical operation has been carried out on his chest, the
official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
According to doctors treating him, the operation has been
successfully performed to pump blood out of the respiratory organ
of the patient and treat injuries caused by the fractured rib
ripping into his lung.
</P>
<P>
The danger to Mazroui's life has been removed and his overall
condition is satisfactory, said the doctors, adding that once the
patient regains consciousness, a decision would be made on ensuing
treatment and period of hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
According to Mazroui's relatives, the road accident occurred as
the car Mazroui was traveling in swerved and hit roadside railing.
The car then overturned.
</P>
<P>
Mazroui was on his way back to Tehran from Rasht, Gilan
Province, where he delivered a speech on the role of the press in
reforms on Tuesday, when the accident took place.
</P>
<P>
Mazroui is a leading member of the Islamic Iran Participation
Front (IIPF), the party which led reformers to an overwhelming
victory in February's parliament election. He was elected into the
sixth Majlis (parliament) from the central province of Isfahan in
the election.
</P>
<P>
Before the February 18 elections, Mazroui served as an economic
advisor to reformist President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Since the parliamentary election, there has been in an air of
growing tension between Iran's political factions representing
reformists and conservatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
