<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 13 Lebanese Detainees to Be Released by Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Israel's prison authority
announced Wednesday that 13 of the 15 Lebanese detainees now in its
custody will be set free by the start of next week.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was issued following an ruling of Israel's
Supreme Court earlier in the day, which ordered immediately release
of eight of the detainees because they have been illegally kept for
years as bargaining chips for missing Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
In the ruling reached by a nine-judge panel with a 6-3 vote, the
court said Israeli law does not give Israeli defense ministry the
authority to hold these Lebanese citizens in administrative
detention as they are not presenting threats to the security of the
country.
</P>
<P>
All these Lebanese hostages are used by Israel as bargaining
cards for information or return of missing Israeli servicemen,
including Ron Arad, an Israeli Air Force navigator who has been
missing since 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Five Lebanese hostages were freed last December and another one
was released by Tel Aviv District Court last week on the grounds of
his deteriorating mental health after long-time detention.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Zvi Rish, the lawyer representing these detainees,
asserted that seven Lebanese prisoners remained in custody should
be let go under the framework of the Supreme Court ruling, although
they did not appeal in the case.
</P>
<P>
Finally, Israel's Prison authority agreed to release five more
of them and said that all 13 detainees will be freed after the
authority reaches a transfer arrangement with the International Red
Cross organization.
</P>
<P>
This means that the two most prominent detainees, Sheik Abdel
Karim Obeid and Mustafa Dirani, will still be held in Israeli
prison without a trial.
</P>
<P>
Obeid, a spiritual leader of Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas, was
kidnapped from his home in south Lebanon in 1989, and Dirani,
security chief of the Lebanese resistance militia Amal, was
captured by Israeli agents in a special operation in 1994.
</P>
<P>
It was Dirani who held Arad after the Israeli navigator
parachuted from his hit Phantom fighter on Lebanese soil in October
1986. Dirani reportedly traded Arad to either Lebanese Hezbollah
guerrillas or Iranian elements later.
</P>
<P>
In response to the court ruling, Israeli Chief of General Staff
Shaul Mofaz said the Israel Defense Forces have objected to the
release of Lebanese detainees due to its moral responsibility to
ensure the return of Arad and other captured Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Now the army would have to learn the details of the closed-door
decision reached by a 6-3 vote before taking any actions, Mofaz
said.
</P>
<P>
He vowed to Arad's family that the defense establishment would
continue its efforts to get Arad back to his homeland.
</P>
<P>
Arad's mother Batia Arad condemned the court decision, saying
she felt betrayed by the court.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Human Rights Organization issued a statement
to welcome the order of release and urge immediately release of all
the Lebanese citizens in Israeli detention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Bolster Economic Cooperation with Egypt: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien told Egypt that his country has the desire to bolster
bilateral cooperation in economy, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Chretien
said Canada is ready to promote relations with Egypt in trade,
vocational training and technology transfer, Moussa told reporters
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that the talks also dealt with the latest
developments of the Middle East peace process and discussed ways of
breaking the deadlock in the Arab-Israeli peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Canada currently provides peacekeepers to the Middle East,
including 180 soldiers stationed on the Israeli-occupied Syrian
Golan Heights, and hosts talks on Palestinian refugees as part of
the multilateral phase of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Chretien arrived here Tuesday night for a three-day visit as
part of a regional tour, which also includes Jordan, the
Palestinian self-rule areas, Israel, Syria, Lebanon and Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, Chretien also held talks with his Egyptian
counterpart Atef Obeid on enhancing bilateral economic and trade
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have agreed to beef up their annual trade
volume from less than 200 million U.S. dollars at present to some 1
billion dollars over the coming five years, Obeid told reporters
after the talks.
</P>
<P>
He called on Canada to open up market to Egypt's textiles and
handicrafts in a bid to reach the target.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' trade volume stood at 176 million dollars in
1999. Canada exports lumber, newsprint and high-technology products
to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Obeid and Chretien capped their talks with the signing of four
cooperation agreements in aid, technology transfer, environmental
protection, agriculture and infrastructural construction.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Canada seek to boost economic and trade cooperation
through forging a free trade agreement and enhance Canada's
contribution to Egypt's development projects, especially in the
field of infrastructure, irrigation and technology transfer.
</P>
</TEXT>
