<HEADLINE> Iranian Court Authorizes Interception of Polluting Oil Tankers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian public court on
Wednesday authorized interception of foreign oil tankers polluting
the Iranian waters in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The court at the Kish Free Trade Zone issued the ruling after
the zone administration complained about the damage on the
environment of the resort island and sought compensation from the
oil tankers, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The ruling also followed a crackdown on smuggled Iraqi oil in
the Gulf by Iran which has been under pressure from the West to do
so.
</P>
<P>
Director for Legal Affairs of the zone Mahmoud Alam said that
the tankers carrying the smuggled oil left behind oil slicks,
polluting the environment and endangering marine life.
</P>
<P>
The zone has reported the issue to the Iranian Ports and
Shipping Organization and provided films and slides to show the
extent of the oil slicks and contamination of water and
environment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Iran's elite Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC) recently
seized a dozen of oil tankers in the Gulf for being involved in the
smuggling and violation of Iranian territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
Iran will not permit the use of Iranian territorial waters for
the smuggling of oil, an IRGC officer stressed.
</P>
<P>
The United States has said that the smuggling of oil enables
Iraq to obtain hard currency outside the U.N.-supervised oil-for-
food program which limits the export volume of Iraqi oil.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since its invasion of Kuwait
in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
