<HEADLINE> Tech Selloff Drags Down Canada's Benchmark Index </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Canada's benchmark index fell
sharply Tuesday as the country's high-tech companies slumped after
a disappointing earnings warning by wireless phone maker Motorola
Inc.
</P>
<P>
The Toronto Stock Exchange 300 composite index (TSE 300) fell
102.91 points, or 1.1 percent, to 9,358.03.
</P>
<P>
Total trading was valued at 4.2 billion Canadian dollars (about
2.9 billion U.S. dollars), with 161 million shares changing hands
on the TSE, compared with a three-month daily average of 215
million.
</P>
<P>
Motorola dragged technology-related companies lower after it
said second-quarter earnings would fall short of analyst estimates.
</P>
<P>
Canada's largest telecommunications firm BCE Inc. fell 6.35
Canadian dollars (about 4.38 U.S. dollars) to 170.65 dollars (
about 117.75 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Networking firm Nortel Networks Corp. closed down 8.10 Canadian
dollars (about 5.59 U.S. dollars) at 170.05 dollars (about 117.33
U.S. dollars
</P>
<P>
Fiber-optics equipment company JDS Uniphase Corp. fell 12
Canadian dollars (about 8.28 U.S. dollars) to 149 dollars (about
102.81 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This was the second day in a row for the tech selloff at the
Toronto Stock Exchange amid concern that some technology stocks
are too expensive given the outlook for profit.
</P>
<P>
But some investors are convinced that technology stocks' slide
in recent weeks won't last.
</P>
<P>
"I definitely think we rally from here," said Brian Acker,
president of Acker Finley Inc. in Toronto. "We are really seeing
some unbelievable value. Technology has to be bought here," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Benchmark index for the first time late last month
broke the milestone record of 10,000 points, only to fall back
because of the fear that the high-tech led surprise rise may be
over-priced.
</P>
<P>
Despite tech fluctuations, the TSE 300 has still gained 11
percent this year, making it the best-performing major index in
North America and the second-best in the world after Sweden's OMX,
according to Canadian newspapers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
