<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Squeezes for More Say on Networking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Union has pushed
for more say in computer networking by announcing a series of
recommendations to improve the functioning of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations, published Wednesday, reflected the EU
concerns over the dominance by the United States and U.S.-based
network solutions over the registry of Internet domain names.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet's capacity to unleash enterprises is beyond
question," said Erkki Liikanen, EU commissioner for the
information society.
</P>
<P>
But the commissioner added that the EU must now show that its
infrastructure can be run fairly and effectively to benefit all
its users.
</P>
<P>
The EU is unsatisfied with the implementation of the agreement
of the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN)
that was reached two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
bloc, proposed to make the election of the ICANN's governing board
a more open and transparent process and to secure funding of the
ICANN in an open manner through the network of recently created
registries for domain names.
</P>
<P>
The commission also raised question about the fact that the
ICANN staff is dominated by U.S. personnel who lack the linguistic
capabilities necessary for a truly international organization.
</P>
<P>
The commission wanted rapid approval of the proposed ".eu" high
level domain.
</P>
<P>
This new domain name will coexist with the 15 national domain
names within the EU and will be available for cross-border
electronic commerce services, European institutions and non-profit
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The EU recommendations were published as part of the union's
continuing efforts to accelerate European access to the Internet
and the EU deems it a top priority if the EU is to successfully
compete in the global e-commerce market.
</P>
<P>
Up until last year, the NSI had held exclusive rights to assign
domain names ending in ".com,.net" and ".org". But the U.S.
Department of Commerce, under pressure from various U.S. and non-U.
S. parties, has allowed competitors into this field.
</P>
<P>
But the NSI has kept control rights of the Internet name
registry which contains every address on the Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Hopes to See More Effective South Role in World Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
Wednesday voiced his belief that the peoples of the developing
South should play a more active and influential part in world
affairs, and said that the upcoming Millennium Summit will be an
opportunity for the South to express itself on major international
political and economic issues.
</P>
<P>
Delivering his speech at the opening ceremony of the first
South Summit here, Annan said, "I have always believed that we,
the peoples of the South, should play a more active and
influential part in world affairs. We could do so with great
benefit to ourselves and to the world as a whole."
</P>
<P>
"But in the last resort, our doing so depends on our own
efforts -- those each nation makes on its own behalf, and those we
make to assist and learn from each other," he said.
</P>
<P>
"To assist that coordination and cooperation is one of the
main purposes of the United Nations Development Program (UNDP),
within which there is a Special Unit for Technical Cooperation
among Developing Countries," he said. "UNDP is making South-South
cooperation a pillar of its new approach."
</P>
<P>
The South Summit came as the largest gathering of heads of
state and government since the founding of the Group of 77 (G-77)
in 1964. The historic event was held less than five months before
the U.N. convocation of the Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
"In less than five months' time, the Millennium Summit will
offer us all a unique chance to mobilize the world's energy behind
a common agenda," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Millennium Assembly and the Millennium Summit will be
convened in early September at the U.N. Headquarters in New York,
which is believed an opportunity to strengthen the U.N. role in
the new century.
</P>
<P>
"In that gathering, the voice of the South will be heard, and
heard good and loud," he said. "But what is even more important is
that the summit should lead to real improvements in people's lives,
especially in those of the poor."
</P>
<P>
"That means the South's voice must not only be loud but clear,
consistent and constructive," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan has presented his Millennium report to the General
Assembly, which lists the choice of priorities on major issues
facing the world at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
As the largest Third World coalition in the United Nations, G-
77 has been an effective negotiating force in the 188-nation world
body to defend the collective interests of the South. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Compensate Stricken Workers at Atomic Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The plan, which has been under development for about a year and
must still be submitted to Congress, follows the acknowledgment by
the Energy Department earlier this year that workers involved in
building the nation's nuclear arsenal showed higher-than-normal
rates of several different kinds of cancer and other ailments,
based on a review of years of scientific studies.
</P>
<P>
The concession opened the door for compensation. Wednesday's
New York Times quoted government sources as saying the plan could
cost 400 million U.S. dollars over the first five years. But costs
would decline as the number of eligible workers declines.
</P>
<P>
Through the cold war and beyond, the Energy Department and its
predecessor agency, the Atomic Energy Commission, denied that
workers had received harmful doses of radiation.
</P>
<P>
And few of the workers qualified for workers' compensation,
because that was designed for sudden injuries that clearly
happened on the job, not ailments developed by chronic exposure.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal being unveiled, the government would assume
workers were exposed to the highest expected level of radiation
associated with their work if actual medical records were not
available.
</P>
<P>
The Energy Department and its contractors routinely opposed
such payments for compensation based on supposed radiation
exposure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EP Rejects GMO Liability Clause </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Parliament
Wednesday rejected major changes to proposed laws governing
genetically-modified organisms (GMOs).
</P>
<P>
The proposed laws could have otherwise made GMO producers
liable for environmental damage.
</P>
<P>
The governments of the European Union member states and the
European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation bloc,
have already agreed to a new authorization procedure for GMOs but
under the EU rules on co-decision, the European Parliament has new
rights to have more say on legislation.
</P>
<P>
The changes to proposed laws were rejected in the 626-member
assembly that met Wednesday in Strasbourg.
</P>
<P>
The changes have been attacked by Europe's biotech industry
which warned that the changes would have negative influence upon
biotech companies already stifled by "intolerable financial and
regulatory burden." They could have cost jobs and forced the
fledgling sector out of Europe altogether.
</P>
<P>
Green Europe members of the parliament, who argued the changes
were needed to protect public health, were disappointed by the
outcome of Wednesday's series vote.
</P>
<P>
Some members of the parliament, backed by consumer lobbies,
wanted to go even further and force those who produce GMOs to be
held liable for any damage they cause, either to the environment
or to public health.
</P>
<P>
The GMO approval process, provisionally agreed by the EU member
states last June, set a 10-year authorization period for new crops,
after which licenses would be reviewed. The process demanded
stricter regulation on labeling and tracking the GMOs through the
food chain.
</P>
<P>
No new genetically-modified crops have been approved in Europe
since April 1998, antagonizing the United States, the world's top
GMO grower. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
