<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales Up in Both EU, Euro Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The volume of retail trade was
up in both the European Union and the euro zone in January this
year, Eurostat reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg-based statistical bureau of the European
community said that the retail sales were up by 3.0 percent for
the 15-nation bloc and up by 2.3 percent in the 11-nation euro
zone, compared with the figures in January last year.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Germany, all EU countries have registered increases,
ranging Spain's 8.6 percent to Italy's 1.1 percent. In Germany,
however, the retail sales fell by 3.2 percent as against January
last year.
</P>
<P>
Compared with December last year, the retail trade was up by 0.
3 percent in both the EU and euro zone.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales fell in Germany for the third consecutive month in
January, by 1.9 percent as against last December.
</P>
<P>
The increase of retail sales has contributed to the economic
growth in the European Union and the euro zone as well. The gross
domestic product grew by 0.8 percent in the European Union and by
0.9 percent in the euro zone in the fourth quarter of last year,
according to Eurostat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
