<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian-Hungarian Battalion Holds Drill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A Romanian-Hungarian joint
battalion Wednesday proceeded to the final phase of the Open
Windows-Ro-2000 drill of troops and transmission.
</P>
<P>
The drill was meant to train the battalion command and troops
for peace-keeping actions, as well as to increase the experience
concerning such operations in keeping with NATO standards.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-six Romanian troops of the Infantry Battalion Arad 191
and sixty-six Hungarian troops of the Hodmezovasharhely Brigade 62,
Battalion 2, participate in the drill.
</P>
<P>
The drill unfolds upon a fictitious scenario in which a
southeast European country -- Colo Republic -- goes under a
military dictatorship after 1991.
</P>
<P>
According to the story, the Colo Republic is currently "
politically, financially and economically isolated because of its
own home and foreign policy." Under OSCE aegis, the joint Romanian-
Hungarian battalion carries on in the Colo Republic a peace-
keeping and humanitarian aid mission in conditions of heavy floods.
</P>
<P>
The two neighboring countries decided to make up the joint
battalion when their defense ministers met in the Hungarian city
of Debrecen in February 1997. The battalion counts 1,000 soldiers,
among whom 500 are Romanians and 500 Hungarians. Its main
objective is to carry out missions of peacekeeping and
humanitarian aid in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The battalion became operational at the end of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
