<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Up to 25,000 Serbs to Return to Kosovo: NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Up to 25,000 Serbs are expected
to return to Kosovo in the coming months, said an official of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that the
figure was an estimate and could be on the optimistic side of it.
</P>
<P>
Between 100,000 and 200,000 Kosovar Serbs have left the
Yugoslav province since last June since the 78-day NATO air
campaign forced out the Yugoslav army and police forces from the
province. The Serbs left for fear of violent revenge by ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The same NATO official said that some 18,000 more ethnic
Albanians were also expected to return.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Western military alliance was keen for Serbs
to return to the province and its peacekeeping forces KFOR in
Kosovo were ready to guarantee their safety.
</P>
<P>
Many Serbs left Kosovo due to justifiable fear of reprisals by
ethnic Albanians but many others had nothing to feel guilty about,
added the official who admitted that the return of Serbs to Kosovo
would be difficult in that the ethnic relations remain tense in
the province.
</P>
<P>
The Serbs remaining in Kosovo are estimated to number 100,000
as against an ethnic Albanian population of 1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached between Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and NATO to end the air campaign, the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia can return some 1,000 officials to Kosovo to guard
Serb monuments and officiate the borders with neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Security Council Resolution 1244 regards Kosovo
as an integral part of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
