<HEADLINE> Greek Prime Minister Announces New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- With the victory in Sunday's
parliamentary elections, Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
Wednesday night announced his new cabinet which is made up of 43
ministers and deputy ministers.
</P>
<P>
The previous cabinet was composed of 19 ministers, one
alternate minister and 21 deputy ministers, and the new cabinet is
composed of 20 ministers, one alternate minister and 22 deputy
ministers.
</P>
<P>
While keeping the ministers of the interior, defense, foreign
affairs, economy, finance, agriculture, environment, public order
and press, Simitis decided to include former Foreign Minister
Theodoros Pangalos as culture minister and former Interior
Minister Alekos Papadopoulos as health and welfare minister.
</P>
<P>
Simitis also appointed Nikos Christodoulakis as development
minister, Petros Ephthimiou as education and religious affair
minister, Athanasios Yiannitsis as labor and social security
minister, Michalis Stathopoulos as justice minister, Christos
Papoutsis as merchant marine minister, George Pashalidis as
Macedonia-Thrace minister, Nikos Sifounakis as Aegean minister,
Christos Verelis as transport and communications minister, and
Mitiades Papaioannou as state minister. 
</P>
