<HEADLINE> Southern African Countries Seek to Sell More Ivory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Sun Huixia
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Four southern African countries
are seeking permission to sell more ivory from the ongoing 11th
conference of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered
Species here, saying that highly controlled ivory trade will
benefit their countries.
</P>
<P>
Botswana delegation head Garyland Kombani told Xinhua on
Wednesday that the habitat for the species became too small since
106,000 elephants in his country occupied an area that could
handle only 50,000.
</P>
<P>
"They are even becoming a danger to themselves due to the
limited food sources and the herd is growing by five percent a
year," Garyland noted.
</P>
<P>
The stocks of ivory are useless if they are not sold and also
cost a lot of money to preserve them, Garyland said.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Zimbabwe delegation Simon Khaya Moyo emphasized the
mutual beneficial relation between humans and elephants.
</P>
<P>
"Habitat for wildlife will only be preserved on a large scale
if this preservation benefit people, and it is therefore
critically important that we reconcile nature and human needs in
ways that serve both humans and wildlife," Moyo said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has demanded an annual quota of 30 tons; Botswana
12 tons; Namibia 2 tons, and Zimbabwe 10 tons.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Botswana, Zimbabwe and Namibia were approved by the
10th CITES meeting to export 59 tons of ivory experimentally to
Japan. The total ban on ivory trade was imposed in 1990 due to a
sharp decline of the elephant population in 1980s.
</P>
<P>
However, Kenya and India strongly oppose relaxing the ivory ban
and demand a return to the total ban.
</P>
<P>
"Kenya would oppose lifting the ban until poaching is brought
under control," Kenyan president Daniel arap Moi said Monday in
his opening statement for the conference.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Wildlife Service said that poaching was on the rise
following the one-off experimental sale of ivory to Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
