<HEADLINE> Britain Supports Congo Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain is determined to play its
part in international efforts to support the peace process in the
war-torn Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), the British High
Commission in Zimbabwe said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to financial support already provided to the Joint
Military Commission and the National dialogue, we are now able to
offer further help, a technical adviser to the Facilitator of the
National Dialogue," the High Commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, Philip Walker, who had worked
extensively in Central Africa over the last 20 years, began his
work in Gaborone, Botswana, this week.
</P>
<P>
Walker would assist the facilitator in all aspects of the
National Dialogue, including helping coordinate support from
international donors, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said, "Britain believes that it is vital that an open and
inclusive inter-Congolese dialogue, as provided for in the Lusaka
Agreement, gets underway soon."
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka cease-fire agreement, which was signed by all
parties involved in the two-year DRC conflict in July and August
last year, seeks to bring peace to the second largest country in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Since August 1998, Zimbabwe, together with other allies, has
deployed troops in the DRC to fight Rwanda and Uganda backed
rebels who are trying to oust the government of President Laurent
Kabila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
