<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Open Skies Idea Criticized by COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) has said that the newly introduced open
skies agreement by the United States may affect the region's
liberalization of air-transport program, the Times of Zambia
newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Open skies agreement permit unrestricted air service by
airlines of different countries to and from the United States and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
The regional grouping would institute measures aimed at
discouraging member states from signing the agreement, said COMESA
Director of infrastructure and development Jerome Ntibarekerwa.
</P>
<P>
He said in an interview in Lusaka on Tuesday that although
progress had been made to fully liberalize the air transport
program which will come into effect in October this year, the
program would not be achieved if member countries sign the open
skies agreement.
</P>
<P>
Liberalization of air transport is important as it would enable
the COMESA member states to promote the growth of regional
economies, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said COMESA would also strengthen the rules and regulations
so that member states can benefit from the air industry
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
"We would soon call a meeting with member states to discuss the
rules and regulations as well as to educate them on the effects of
entering into an agreement with open skies agreement," the
director was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Africans should not allow situations where a plane coming from
the United States comes and picks people from three African
countries. This would make the air program ineffective," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the only answer to the investment opportunities in the
COMESA region is to implement the liberalization of air transport.
</P>
<P>
COMESA is now working with relevant authorities and the
region's airlines on a program to remove air traffic controls,
with the aim of eventual removal of all air traffic controls
except for those concerned with safety.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the COMESA interim air transport regulatory board
meeting is scheduled to take place in two weeks' time in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to discuss the way forward for the air
transport.
</P>
<P>
The countries that constitute the board are Zambia, Egypt,
Ethiopia, Namibia, Sudan and Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
