<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Urged to Improve Indigenization Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe needs to improve
implementation of the indigenization policy by developing an
action plan to expedite the empowerment process, said Minister of
State Cephas Msipa on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at the signing ceremony of a research project
on the state of indigenization between the ministry and the
Scientific Industrial Research and Development Centre.
</P>
<P>
The action plan could only be formulated after determining the
achievements and constraints to the indigenization process so far,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The research study, he said, would give the indeginization
process the necessary direction to effectively realize the
expectations of the action plan.
</P>
<P>
The study would also establish indicators to provide relevant
information for proposing the way forward in putting in place
specific policy measures and incentives, he said.
</P>
<P>
"After the launching of the policy framework on indigenization
in February 1998, it is crucial that we undertake a survey to find
out where the indigenous Zimbabweans are in terms of participation
in the mainstream economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, information from the study would be
useful to the government and indigenization lobby groups.
</P>
<P>
The government is working out legislative incentives to promote
 implementation of an employee stock ownership scheme to accord
workers a stake in the companies they work for, he said.
</P>
<P>
He commended some large corporations which had come up with
their own programs to help develop an indigenous private sector.
</P>
