<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Industry Urged to Be Export-Oriented </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Finance Minister
Herbert Murerwa Wednesday urged the country's industry to be
export-oriented to earn more foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inauguration of the Export Credit Guarantee
Corporation (ECGC) in Harare, the minister said, "a buoyant export
sector is vital for any economy to realize its growth and
development potential for it is through exporting that we
guarantee adequate foreign exchange flows into the economy," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In the absence of adequate foreign currency generation, he
said, Zimbabwe is severely constrained in its ability to realize
full productive potential as the country relies heavily on
imported machinery and raw materials for production.
</P>
<P>
"The government is cognizant of the fact that exports are not
only important simply for their contribution to foreign exchange
inflows, but also because of their key role in a country's
industrialization process," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said as an export promotion agency with an intention of
introducing private participation and owned by the Reserve Bank of
Zimbabwe, ECGC would increase its focus towards reinsurance,
market research and the securing of lines of credit to support
export business.
</P>
<P>
The corporation would assist the government to achieve the
objectives of stabilizing the Zimbabwean dollar and resolving the
foreign currency crisis prevailing in the economy, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
