<HEADLINE> Ten Cult Members Jailed in Northern Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- About 10 cult members of the
Minevam sect have been imprisoned in the northern prefecture of
Byumba, Rwanda, following their illegal operations in the area,
Rwanda News Agency reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to commander of Byumba Police Station Jean de dieu
Gashiramanga, "the believers were arrested following their illegal
mode of operation. The group is mainly composed of females."
</P>
<P>
He said some of the believers were convinced that God was soon
coming, with students abandoning schools and others giving up
work.
</P>
<P>
The cult also accommodated people from different areas of the
country and others from Uganda, without informing concerned
authorities, which is in contravention of the law, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Minister of Justice and Institutional Relations Jean
de Dieu Mucyo disclosed that "religious sects without registration
should not be allowed to operate because it is such that propagate
dubious teachings based on personal gains."
</P>
<P>
"Prefects and other local authorities should be very keen on
knowing and following up all religious sects' activities in their
areas of jurisdiction, " the minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
Recently, some religious sects in Rwanda have been encouraging
their followers not to do anything apart from praying because the
end of the world is imminent and many believers sold off their
belongings. 
</P>
