<HEADLINE> Emergency Food Airlifted to Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A Hercules C-130 plane,
belonging to the International Committee of Red Cross (ICRC)
landed Wednesday at Gode Airport, about 600 km southeast of Addis
Ababa, airlifting 15 tons of emergency food.
</P>
<P>
ICRC said in a press release that the emergency operation is
due to last at least till the end of June and will help people
most affected by the drought in Somali State.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, the assistance provided by the ICRC
for the first two months of the operation represents a total of
4,512 tons, which will be airlifted every day from Nairobi,
Kenya, to Gode Airport and will subsequently be delivered by road
to all communities of the four affected districts.
</P>
<P>
"This assistance consists in rations of pre-cooked food
including maize, soya and sugar as well as oil which will come as
an essential complement to the wheat already distributed by the
Ethiopian Disaster Preparedness and Prevention Commission
(DPPC)," the release added. 
