<HEADLINE> Turkish Peacekeepers Back Home from Bosnia- Herzegovina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The last Turkish troops which
carried out peacekeeping mission in Bosnia-Herzegovina returned
home Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 180-member unit, the final batch of a 1,500-strong Turkish
presence there, was welcomed at the Derince Harbor, in Marmara,
northwest of Turkey, with a military ceremony, the Anatolia News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony, Aydin Sen, the 15th Army Corps
commander, said that the unit accomplished its peacekeeping mission
with success, and contributed to maintaining peace and security in
the war-torn former Yugoslavia republic.
</P>
<P>
Following Bosnia-Herzegovina's war for independence, a Turkish
offer of troops to the U.N. Protection Force in Bosnia was at first
rejected by the U.N. Security Council because of Ankara's strong
sympathies with Bosnian Muslims.
</P>
<P>
In April 1994, however, after experiencing difficulties in
recruiting enough army commitments, the U.N. allowed Turkey to
deploy about 1,500 soldiers in spite of objections by Bosnian
Serbs. 
</P>
