<HEADLINE> Estrada Insists on Probe on Tax Credit Scam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has ordered that the investigation into a multi-billion-
peso tax credit scam should continue full-blast even if it would
implicate his friends in the case, Philippine News Agency said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora was quoted as saying
Wednesday that the president sees no reason to stop the
investigation, even with reports alleging that his friend Dane Tan
benefited from the tax credit scam.
</P>
<P>
"The president's instruction was to proceed with the probe
regardless of who is linked to it. He wants the probe to go on and
he wants results," Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
He said Task Force 156, which was created by the president to
investigate the anomalies involving the issuance of fake tax
credit certificates during the past administration, has so far
uncovered the involvement of former officials of the Department of
Finance and oil firms and other large corporations in the scam.
</P>
<P>
"We have so far confirmed 4.5 billion pesos (112 million U.S.
dollars) in anomalies. As can be gleaned from the documents with
us,perhaps the amount involved would reach 8 billion pesos (200
million dollars)," Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
Those who would eventually be implicated in the scam already
knew the risks they were taking and would have no one else to
blame, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
