<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF: World Economy to Grow 4.2 Percent in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The world economy is expected
to grow 4.2 percent this year and slow to 3.9 percent in 2001, the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The IMF, in its twice-yearly World Economic Outlook, said
global growth is now estimated to have reached 3.3 percent in 1999
compared with a projection of only 2.2 percent prepared at the end
of 1998, at the height of financial market turbulence and the low
point in the associated confidence crisis.
</P>
<P>
"North America and the emerging market countries of Asia
account for much of the stronger growth picture but other regions
also contribute," the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
It said the global downturn in the wake of the crises in Asia
and other emerging market countries since 1997 now appears to have
been relatively mild and brief.
</P>
<P>
"Evidence of a strong rebound in the global economy has
continued to accumulate in recent months and the momentum of the
recovery from the 1997-98 slowdown has proven much stronger than
anticipated," the IMF said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Updated With More Details) IMF Sees World Economy Growing 4.2 Percent in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In its twice-yearly World Economic Outlook, the IMF said global
growth is now estimated to have reached 3.3 percent in 1999
compared with a projection of only 2.2 percent prepared at the end
of 1998, at the height of financial market turbulence and the low
point in the associated confidence crisis.
</P>
<P>
The release of the IMF's economic outlook marked the start of
several days of preliminary events leading to the formal opening
of the IMF and World Bank's spring meetings Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"North America and the emerging market countries of Asia
account for much of the stronger growth picture but other regions
also contribute," the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
It said the global downturn in the wake of the crises in Asia
and other emerging market countries since 1997 now appears to have
been relatively mild and brief.
</P>
<P>
"Evidence of a strong rebound in the global economy has
continued to accumulate in recent months and the momentum of the
recovery from the 1997-98 slowdown has proven much stronger than
anticipated," the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF, which had been forced by the 1997-98 currency crisis
to consistently lower its forecasts, said it is now in the
pleasant position of boosting its estimates, largely because of
the continued unexpected strength in the United States.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF cautioned that a sudden plunge in the U.S.
stock market and a "hard landing" for the U.S. economy is one of
the leading risks to its forecast.
</P>
<P>
It mentioned threats from a sudden plunge in the U.S. stock
market that would shake consumer confidence, and the country's
huge and growing trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Japan's recovery from its long recession was "tentative and
fragile" and Europe had to ensure it did not kill off an upturn
with unnecessary rate rises.
</P>
<P>
The IMF, noting that the dollar appeared overvalued against
Europe's single currency, the euro, also said it was worried about
"significant misalignments" of several key currencies and about "
very high stock market valuations."
</P>
<P>
External imbalances around the world were also a cause for
concern, primarily the wide U.S. current account deficit and
persistently large surpluses in Japan, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The IMF also said Britain and Canada would need to tighten
monetary policy to contain inflationary pressures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
