<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BoE Chief Casts Doubt On Euro Timing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Eddie George, governor of the Bank
of England, has said that membership of the first wave of the
single currency would have put the UK's record-breaking economic
performance at risk.
</P>
<P>
It would be best for Britain to stay out until there was
greater convergence between the UK and the Euroland economy, he
told a business audience in Bradfor Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The governor said, "If we had joined EMU from the start and had
Eurozone interest rates over the past year or so, it is very
difficult to envisage how we could have avoided an inflationary
boom in this country."
</P>
<P>
He said there had been some disappointment but also
considerable relief at the decision since Britain "could have been
the elephant in the rowing boat."
</P>
<P>
His speech came as the European Commission admitted that the
euro will be a lame duck on the international exchanges for at
least two years
</P>
<P>
George also insisted that scrapping the pound was "
fundamentally a political rather than an economic issue" which
would mean giving up control over "important aspects of public
policy."
</P>
<P>
His view is significant because the government's tests for
assessing whether to join the euro after the next election,
expected in 2001 or 2002, require "sustainable convergence."
</P>
<P>
This is the second time the governor has appeared skeptical. In
December last year, he said the City of London had "thrived" since
the euro's launch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
