<HEADLINE> Canadian E-commerce Company Reports Security Breach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A Vancouver-based Canadian cable
and Internet company has reported a security breach to its
customer credit card and accounts, the country's National Post
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that the breach, which was discovered on
Monday, involved as many as 1,300 customer accounts belonging to
Internet service provider -- idirect.com -- owned by Look
Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
Personal information on credit card numbers and users'
passwords were accessible on the Internet, said the report.
</P>
<P>
"They were all Canadian accounts and the company has taken
steps to shut down the leak," Al Finn, director of risk security
at Visa Canada, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Look Communications has called in Deloitte and Touche
consultants to assess the damage done to its business, Finn added.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time in the past two months that a Canadian
e-commerce company has reported a security breach.
</P>
<P>
Last month, an international police investigation led to the
arrests of two 18-year-old computer hackers in Wales, who were
found to have stolen information on 23,000 credit card holders
from web sites, including one belonging to a Toronto company, the
newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
