<HEADLINE> Haider Arrives in Brussels for EU Committee Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Austrian far-right leader Joerg
Haider arrived here on Wednesday, amidst protests at the airport,
for a European Union (EU) regional committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
Haider, whose party's integration into the Austrian coalition
government has sustained strong opposition from across the EU,
arrived three hours ahead of schedule to shun organized protests.
</P>
<P>
Haider is expected to attend the 33rd EU regional committee
meeting as governor of Austria's Carinthia State.
</P>
<P>
Austria has been isolated by its 14 EU partners since Wolfgang
Schuessel struck a power-sharing deal with Haider's Freedom Party
early February.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian authorities tightened security at the airport to
ensure that nothing should go wrong with Haider's arrival. Haider
canceled his trip to Brussels last month due to anti-facist
demonstrations around the Austrian embassy and the EU regional
committee headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Austria's EU partners agreed early February to isolate Austria,
refusing to promote or accept any bilateral official contacts with
it at political level and giving no support for Austrian
candidates seeking positions in international institutions; thus
Austrian ambassadors in EU capitals will only be received at a
technical level.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, one of several EU member states that strongly oppose
to the integration of Haider's far-right party into Austria's
coalition government, warned that the integration would be a
dangerous precedent to incorporate the extreme rightists into any
EU government.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
bloc, said it would follow carefully the development in Austria,
urging Austria to fully and properly apply all EU rules and laws.
</P>
<P>
Haider has resigned from the leadership of the Freedom Party
though some critics argued that he made the move in order to
advance in future toward the post of federal chancellor that is
now being held by Schuessel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Interest Rates Raised by 0.25 Percent in Norway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Norwegian central bank
Wednesday raised its key interest rates for loans to commercial
banks by 0.25 percent to 5.75 percent in a bid to counter
inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks also raised their day-to-day loan rate from 7.
5 to 7.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time the Norges Bank has raised its key rates
since August 1998. The rates, staying as high as 8 percent in
January 1999, had been cut five times till September.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that this move is in response to a forecast on
economic growth higher than the previous one, which might bring
about more inflation.
</P>
<P>
In March, the central bank revised the projected economic
growth for this year to 1.5 percent, nearly doubling the previous
figure. The forecast inflation rate was also raised to 2.75
percent, 0.5 percent higher than the previous figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
