<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First South Summit Opens in Havana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The first South Summit opened on
Wednesday at the Havana International Conference Center in the
largest gathering of heads of state and government since the
establishment of the Group of 77 (G-77) in 1964.
</P>
<P>
The summit, scheduled to end on April 14, was held in
accordance with the decision adopted by the 21st Ministerial
Meeting of the G-77 in September 1997 at the United Nations
headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
Cuban President Fidel Castro and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, among other leaders, are to address the opening ceremony
chaired by Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo, whose country
holds the G-77 chairmanship for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, leaders will focus on the broad themes of
globalization, knowledge and technology, South-South cooperation
and North-North relations.
</P>
<P>
The summit meeting opened following preparatory meetings of
senior officials and foreign ministers from 133 G-77 member states
in the developing South.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 heads of state or government, along with 70 foreign
ministers and other senior officials, including their respective
ambassador to Cuba, gathered in Havana for the summit.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said that 122 member countries have sent delegations,
as had 34 non-member countries and 36 international organizations,
such as the United Nations and the Non-align Movement.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier Li Lanqing, head of the Chinese government
delegation, was present at the opening ceremony. China has long
been in close ties with G-77, and Cuban Foreign Minister Felipe
Perez Roque, at a press conference here on Monday, spoke highly of
China's support for the group.
</P>
<P>
From the South Summit will emerge two final documents -- the
Havana Declaration and the Program of Action. The forward-looking
declaration will set out a vision and broad strategy for the
future while the action-oriented program will clearly define
measures, targets and time frames for implementation, G-77
officials said.
</P>
<P>
G-77 was founded on June 15, 1964 by 77 developing countries in
Geneva. Although its current membership has increased to 133
countries, the original name was retained because of its historic
significance.
</P>
<P>
As the largest Third World coalition in the United Nations and
the largest grouping in the South, the organization provides means
for the developing world to articulate and promote its collective
economic interests and enhance its joint negotiating capacity on
all major international economic issues in the United Nations
system, and promote economic and technical cooperation among
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's State Duma Blames PACE for Suspending Russia's Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Russia's State Duma (lower house
of the parliament) on Wednesday condemned a resolution of the
Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe (PACE) to suspend
Russia's membership.
</P>
<P>
A statement passed by 383 support votes, 3 against and one
abstention, said that "PACE sanctions, limitation of rights and
unilateral dictation toward Russia are unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
The Russian parliamentarians said the "unfounded and unjust"
resolution was attempted to limit the Russian delegation's voting
power.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma said that the resumption of full-scale
cooperation between Russia and PACE is possible only after the
latter abandons the "discriminatory position" on Russia.
</P>
<P>
Last week, PACE voted for limiting the Russian delegation's
rights and initiating suspension proceedings against Russia's
membership in the Council of Europe.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma also expressed its support for the position of
the Russian delegation at PACE's spring session, describing the
delegation's decision to withdraw from the session as "justified."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement said Russia's operation in the North
Caucasus is aimed at "restoration of democracy and human rights in
the Chechen Republic, as well as preservation of territorial
integrity and constitutional system of the Russian Federation."
</P>
</TEXT>
