<HEADLINE> Arabs Slam Israeli Settlement Expansion on Golan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League Secretary General
Esmat Abdel-Meguid on Wednesday lashed out at an Israeli decision
to expand settlement on the Golan Heights as "a provocative act"
that will obstruct the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said in a statement that the construction of new
housing units on the strategic plateau that Israel captured from
Syria in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war "blocks the windows" of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israel said on Tuesday that it had approved the building of 200
more homes on the Golan as it foresaw no early resumption of
negotiations with Damascus on the return of the heights.
</P>
<P>
"This new step is provocative and does not help in creating an
atmosphere of trust to restart the peace process in the region,"
the Arab League chief said.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Israel resumed peace negotiations last December after
a break of around four years, but the talks were suspended in
January because of their dispute over the Golan.
</P>
<P>
Syria demands Israeli commitment to a full withdrawal from the
plateau, while Israel rejects it. All efforts to revive the talks
have failed so far.
</P>
<P>
There are about 18,000 Jewish settlers on the heights.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid called on Russia, the United Nations and the United
States to play a more effective role in pressuring Israel to
respect the principles of peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
