<HEADLINE> Iranians Protest Nullifying of Election Result </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Some 200 Iranian people held a
rally before the Interior Ministry in Tehran on Wednesday to
protest a decision made by the Guardians Council (GC) to nullify
certain votes of the sixth parliamentary elections held in
February.
</P>
<P>
The protesters, who had traveled to Tehran from the northwestern
city of Khalkhal, were carrying placards denouncing the GC for
nullifying the votes of 21 ballot boxes, thereby changing the
election result in the constituency, the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
They called on the Interior Ministry to send a special team to
investigate the so-called vote rigging that is definitely
unfounded, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of people have been jailed in Khalkhal following protests
by angry residents in the city since last Thursday, when the
conservative GC overturned results from city voting booths,
depriving a reformist candidate of victory and handing it to his
conservative rival.
</P>
<P>
Reformers supporting President Mohammad Khatami won more than 75
percent of the seats in the new parliament in a landslide victory
which humiliated the powerful conservatives.
</P>
<P>
The election results have caused political tension in Iran. And
recent events, including the abortive assassination attempt against
prominent reformer, Saeed Hajjarian, and the summoning of famous
reformist journalists by the press court, make people worry about
the country's political future.
</P>
<P>
The GC, as the watchdog of the elections, has not yet approved
the soundness of the first-round election results in 28
constituencies involving some 60 candidates.
</P>
<P>
Those constituencies include the capital Tehran, where reformers
seized at least 29 of the 30 seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
