<HEADLINE> Pakistan, India to Hold Talks on Railway Service  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani and Indian officials
have agreed to meet on April 14 at their border to discuss matters
relating the railway service connecting the two countries,
Pakistani officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of Pakistan Railways Javed Ashraf disclosed this and
expressed his welcome to the agreement in an interview with the
state-run Associated Press of Pakistan (APP) here.
</P>
<P>
He said senior officials of the two countries will be meeting
on Friday at Zero Line of the border in Wagha, 30 kilometers east
of Pakistan's second largest city, Lahore.
</P>
<P>
"This is a matter of satisfaction that Indian Railways
authorities have realized the need of strictly complying with the
1991 agreement between the two countries on the Samjhota Express,"
Ashraf said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed in 1991, India and Pakistan agreed
to jointly operate the Samjhota Express, the only railway link
between the two South Asian neighbors, each for six months in a
year.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Railways discontinued its service in May 1994 on the
ground that smuggling and terrorism were carried out via the cross-
border railway service.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Samjhota Express has been running by Pakistan
Railways only,according to APP.
</P>
<P>
Recently Pakistan Railways, via the Pakistani Foreign Office,
informed India that it would also stop the service if India
refuses to discuss the matter before April 15, 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
