<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Row Erupts over Aid to India's Tiger Conservation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Sun Huixia
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A report by wildlife experts has
 recommended that financial assistance to tiger conservation in
India be cut off unless the south Asian country shows it is
efficient in using money to protect the big cat.
</P>
<P>
Despite millions of dollars in aid, India's wild tiger
population is being heavily poached, apparently by gangs of
organized and well-funded hunters, according to a newly released
report by wildlife experts working for the Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES).
</P>
<P>
However, Indian officials attending the CITES meeting said here
on Wednesday that the recommendation could do great harm to tiger
conservation in India, which hosts about half of the population.
</P>
<P>
"We need financial support in order to continue tiger
conservation. If financial aid is suspended, the team that
prepared the report will be responsible for the illegal killing of
tigers in the future," head of the Indian delegation Suresh Sharma
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Sharma claimed that the report portrayed an unfairly bleak
picture of tiger conservation in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We have done what we can on the basis of the available
resources and our country has generally gone beyond what CITES has
recommended in protecting the big cat," he said.
</P>
<P>
The report will be discussed in the coming few days of the
CITES conference, which lasts from April 10 through 20.
</P>
<P>
Wild tigers are under severe threat from habitat loss and
poaching, plummeting from over 100,000 in the 19th century to just
5,000 to 7,000 now, ranging from India and Russia to China and
some southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Environmental groups argue that one of the greatest threat to
the wild tiger is illegal hunting and the effective way to curb
poaching is to stop the use of tiger parts as medicine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Ivory Stocks Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe currently holds 24 tons
of ivory in stockpiles, which have been increasing since 1997,
according to a report available at the ongoing international
meeting here.
</P>
<P>
The report, prepared by Zimbabwean Ministry of Mines,
Environment and Tourism and made available at the 11th meeting of
the Conference of the Parties to the Convention on International
Trade in Endangered Species (CITES), highlights the sources of
the stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
The report reveals the country's ivory status from 1997 to
1999, saying that most of the stocks are under the Department of
National Parks and Wildlife Management.
</P>
<P>
It says that the increase of ivory stocks since 1997 is
attributed to " continuous increase of elephant population coupled
with a high rate of recovery of ivory from natural mortality."
</P>
<P>
The increase is also a result of problem animal control
recoveries, that is, elephants are shot because they pose a
problem when they invade communal land due to increased
population, the report says.
</P>
<P>
Other sources of ivory stocks include the confiscated poached
ivory and insignificant amount of legal hunting.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe had an elephant population of 70,000 in 1999 as
against 43,000 in 1987.
</P>
<P>
"With or without culling, ivory will continue to be produced
from well managed elephant herd in southern Africa and the
product has to be marketed to the best of the advantage of the
Range states." the reported added.
</P>
<P>
At the ongoing CITES meeting, Zimbabwe, together with Botswana,
Namibia and South Africa, have proposed a further authorization
for trade in elephant products under strict conditions.
</P>
<P>
The CITES meeting, held in Zimbabwe's capital Harare in 1997,
agreed Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe could make a one-time and
highly-controlled experimental sale of their existing ivory
stocks to Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
