<HEADLINE> S.Africa to Publish Result of Probes in Insider Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Johannesburg
Stock Exchange (JSE) is considering making public results of
internal inquiries into possible insider trading, according to JSE
surveillance technical advisor Peter Redman.
</P>
<P>
Redman was quoted on Wednesday by South African Press
Association as saying that in the interest of transparency the JSE
could soon announce the names of companies it had contacted as a
result of abnormal price and volume movements.
</P>
<P>
Redman said this information, as well as company responses to
the inquiries, could be published on a weekly basis.
</P>
<P>
On a monthly basis, he said the JSE could also be making public
details of investigations carried out as well as of issues passed
on to statutory industry watchdog, the Financial Services Board
(FSB).
</P>
<P>
Redman said that in common with other major bourses around the
globe, directors of JSE-listed companies could soon also be
required to disclose " within a short time period" all trades they
had made with their companies' shares.
</P>
<P>
He said there were already rules in place aimed explicitly at
eliminating the manipulation of share prices and volumes to
deceive the market about the nature and liquidity of shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
