<HEADLINE> Russia to Further Participate in International Space Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Russia will continue to take part
in international space programs while pushing forward national
aerospace industry by every means, said Russian President-elect
Vladimir Putin on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Mir space station must be preserved and Russia will
further its participation in international space cooperation
programs and fulfill all its international commitments, Putin said
at a meeting with Russian cosmonauts and managers of the Russian
space industry in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
However, "the main accent" must be put on the Russian
manufacturers, he said. "The rocket and space industry
is not only a prestigious industrial branch which is making Russia
a great power, but is also an industry which deals with the most
daring and reasonable economic projects," he said.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Russian Aerospace Agency Director Yuri
Koptev told the press that the Russian space programs in 2000 will
include manned flights and replacement of some satellites.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Space Program for 2001-2005 signed by Putin on
March 30 "recognizes our needs and potential," he added.
</P>
<P>
Russia's 110 satellites account for one fifth of all the
spacecraft now in orbit, Koptev said. "We make thorough use of
them. No other country has such a vast experience of space
exploration," he said.
</P>
<P>
April 12 is Russia's Cosmonautics Day marking the 39th
anniversary of the launch of Russian cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin into
space, the first in the world.
</P>
<P>
Putin congratulated Russian cosmonauts and leaders of the
Russian space industry on Cosmonautics Day, saying it is "a
legendary holiday not only for Russia, but also for the whole of
mankind."
</P>
<P>
He expressed thanks to "the outstanding people and outstanding
scientific and technical achievements."
</P>
<P>
He said the Russian Security Council is likely to consider the
development of the Russian space industry at one of its future
meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
