<HEADLINE> Diplomatic News Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Following are highlights of today
's diplomatic news released by Xinhua:
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Leaves for Five-Nation Trip
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin left here by special plane to
kick off his state visit to Israel, Palestine, Turkey, Greece and
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Jiang is on the visit at the invitation of President Ezer
Weizman of the State of Israel, President Yasser Arafat of the
State of Palestine, President Suleyman Demirel of the Republic of
Turkey, President Costis Stephanopoulos of the Republic of Greece,
and President Thabo Mbeki of the Republic of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Jiang will also go to Alexandria, Egypt, to
meet with President Muhammed Hosni Mubarak of the Arab Republic of
Egypt at Mubarak's invitation.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese Vice-President Meets Madagascar Guests
</P>
<P>
Vice-President Hu Jintao said here that China is pleased with
the growth of its relations with Madagascar.
</P>
<P>
Hu, a Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee, made the remark
during a meeting with a delegation of the Party of Action for
Madagascar's Renaissance led by its National Secretary Pierrot
Rajaonarivelo.
</P>
<P>
He noted that bilateral relations have been developing
continuously since the forging of diplomatic ties in 1972, and
that an exchange of high-level visits have been frequent, while
bilateral cooperation in a variety of areas has been expanding.
</P>
<P>
 Singaporean PM Visits Xi'an
</P>
<P>
Singaporean Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong expressed his hope
here that Shannxi Province in northwest China would return to its
former glory in the forthcoming development of western China.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks while meeting with Li Jianguo, secretary
of the Shaanxi Provincial Committee of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
Li also expressed the hope that cooperation will be increased
between Shaanxi and Singapore as the province continues its
development, mostly in the field of science and technology.
