<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Meets Canadian Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak met
on Wednesday with Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien and
discussed
the Middle East peace process and bilateral economic issues.
</P>
<P>
No details of their talks were immediately available, but
Canadian embassy officials said Chretien would sound out Mubarak's
views on the Arab-Israeli peace talks and discuss how Canada can
help cement peace in the region after a comprehensive agreement is
reached.
</P>
<P>
Canada currently provides peacekeepers to the Middle East,
including 180 soldiers on the Israeli-occupied Syrian Golan
Heights,
and hosts talks on Palestinian refugees as part of the multilateral
phase of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian officials meanwhile said the two leaders would also
discuss bilateral relations and economic ties.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume stood at 176 million U.S. dollars in 1999
between the two countries, decreasing by 8.19 percent from 1998.
Canada exports lumber, newsprint and high-technology products to
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Chretien arrived in Cairo Tuesday night for a three-day visit as
part of a regional tour, which also includes Syria, Lebanon,
Jordan, the Palestinian self-rule areas, Israel and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, Chretien also held talks with Egyptian Prime
Minister Atef Obeid. They capped the talks with the signing of four
pacts in aid, technology transfer, environmental protection,
agriculture and infrastructural construction.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Canada seek to boost economic and trade cooperation
through forging a free trade agreement and Canada's contribution to
Egypt's development projects, especially in the field of
infrastructure, irrigation and technology transfer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
