<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Preliminary data issued by Yemen's Central Agency For
Statistics showed that Yemeni trade of balance had a surplus of 67.
2 billion rials (420 million U.S. dollars) at the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to data and figures published Wednesday in the local
newspapers, the United Arab Emirates was ranked first among Arab
countries in terms of commercial exchanges with Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Yemen's imports from the UAE amounted to 37.9 billion rials
(236.9 million dollars), against exports of 26.8 billion rials
(167.5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Yemeni balance of trade achieved a surplus with Asian
countries estimated at 260.9 billion rials (1.63 billion dollars)
due to Yemen's exports of oil, gas and derivatives to China, South
Korea, Singapore, India, Turkey and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran exported 10,000 tons of steel products worth 3
million dollars to France on Tuesday, the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This is the first consignment of hot rolled steel sheets that
France has ordered from Mobarakeh Steel Complex in central Iran's
Isfahan province, Ali Reza Moazam, managing director of the complex
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said the complex had exported over 639,000 tons of various
kinds of steel valued at 101 million dollars to different countries
in the last Iranian year which ended March 19.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran exported about 20,000 tons of kiwi fruit worth 10
million dollars in the last Iranian year that ended on March 19,
the Islamic Republic News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The fruit was mainly exported to Asia, Eastern Europe, Africa
and South America, according to Abdol Majid Amir-Ebrahimi, head of
Iran's Kiwi Growers Association.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran produced about 40,000 tons of kiwi fruit from 2,000
hectares of land under cultivation last year.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan became on Tuesday the 136th member in the World
Trade Organization, 30 days after it was notified of the
endorsement of the membership decision taken by the WTO.
</P>
<P>
The Arab economic daily Al Alam El-Yom quoted Wednesday the
director of international organizations in the Jordanian Ministry
of Trade and Industry, Tamam el-Ghoul, as saying Jordan's entry
came after the country had completed its negotiations which started
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi bankers expected that Saudi Arabia will achieve
a surplus of 4 billion rials (1.07 billion dollars) in its budget
by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi daily "Eliqtisadiya" on Wednesday quoted the chief
economist of the Saudi National Bank Abdulla Said el-Sheikh as
estimating the country's oil revenues during the current year at
147 billion rials (39.2 billion dollars) while non-oil revenues
will amount to 49 billion rials (13.1 billion dollars), with the
volume of spending expected to reach 185 billion rials (49.3
billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
