<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in India Triples in 1990s: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The flow of foreign direct
investment (FDI) into India tripled during the 1990s despite its
decrease in the Asia-Pacific region during the decade, a report by
the U.N. Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
While the Asia-Pacific region's share in the world's annual
average FDI flows dropped to 18 percent from 20 percent in the
past decade, India's share had tripled to 3.3 percent from 1.1
percent in 1991, the Press Trust of India quoted UNCTAD as saying
in its World Investment Directory 2000.
</P>
<P>
The annual average FDI flows to India in the 1990s expanded
more than six times, rising from 470 million U.S. dollars between
1991 and 1994 to 2.7 billion dollars between 1995 and 1998 and
reaching a peak of 3.6 billion dollars in 1997, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The flow of FDI slowed down once during the decade in 1998, in
the wake of that year's financial crisis in Asia, the document
said, adding that preliminary estimates for 1999 showed that
inflows had remained stable.
</P>
<P>
India enjoys even greater potential for higher FDI growth in
the near future, the document predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
