<HEADLINE> Pakistan GDP Growth Expected at 4.4 Pct: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The economic situation is
stable in Pakistan with GDP growth expected to reach 4.4 percent
and inflation to be around 4 percent in the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's Finance Secretary General Moeen Afzal and Governor
of State Bank of Pakistan Ishart Hussain told a joint press
briefing here Wednesday that the short-term economic scenario
seems to be comfortable.
</P>
<P>
However, they noted that the government will have to take
sustained measures to achieve economic stability in the medium
term.
</P>
<P>
They said that by the end of June the GDP growth is estimated
to be 4.4 percent, higher than the 3.1 percent in the previous
fiscal year and the inflation rate will be contained at 4 percent
against the set target of 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign exchange reserve position has been stable
at around 1.5 billion U.S. dollars since the setup of the military
government in October last year, according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
As far as revenue collection is concerned, the officials said
the revised figure of 362 billion rupees (6.96 billion dollars)
will be achieved, showing an remarkable improvement compared with
the figure of the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
