<HEADLINE> India, Germany Start Strategic Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- India and Germany opened here
on Wednesday their first-ever "strategic dialogue."
</P>
<P>
The Indo-German strategic dialogue discussed at length some
major issues like the need for concerted international efforts to
combat terrorism and drug trafficking and on disarmament and non-
proliferation, said Ischinger.
</P>
<P>
Ischinger and his Indian counterpart, Lalit Mansingh, said such
dialogue would take place biannually and alternately in the two
countries to demonstrate their intention to work more closely in
the bilateral and international spheres.
</P>
<P>
Ischinger called for intense negotiations on air traffic
between the two countries and the establishment of a "green card"
system to allow German businesses to hire highly qualified Indian
software engineers.
</P>
<P>
The German government was set to open its doors to Indian
information specialists and the German industry could absorb 10,
000 or even more Indian experts in the information technology (IT)
sector, said Ischinger.
</P>
<P>
The Indian authorities had assured him that the German need for
IT specialists could be easily met, he added.
</P>
<P>
Describing 2000 as a "German year in India," Ischinger said
India would be the first stop for the first-ever visit to Asia by
Germany's new Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer next month.
</P>
<P>
In September, German Federal President Johannes Rau will also
pay a state visit to India and open the first-ever German cultural
festival to be held in India, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
