<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Displeased With Ishihara's Anti-Foreigner Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro
Mori on Wednesday expressed discomfort at Tokyo Governor Shintaro
Ishihara's use of a discriminatory term against people from Taiwan
and Korea and for suggesting that foreigners may riot after a
major quake.
</P>
<P>
"If Mr. Ishihara... did indeed use the term as Tokyo governor,
it may have been inappropriate," Mori told reporters while
referring to Ishihara's use of the word "sankokujin," a derogatory
term mainly referring to people from Taiwan and Korea and their
descendants.
</P>
<P>
"Atrocious crimes have been committed again and again by
sankokujin and other foreigners. We can expect them to riot in the
event of a disastrous earthquake," Ishihara said Sunday while
addressing members of Japan's Ground Self-Defense Force (GSDF).
</P>
<P>
Ishihara also called on the GSDF to control the possible riot
by foreigners following a major earthquake.
</P>
<P>
Ishihara came under fire from various fields including Japanese
government officials, opposition parties and the South Korean
government.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, some 40 people, mainly from local assemblies and
civil groups, held a rally in a yard in front of the Tokyo
Metropolitan Government building to protest Ishihara's remarks.
</P>
<P>
They handed metropolitan employees protest leaflets, in which
they demanded Ishihara retract his remarks or step down.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a group of celebrities, including television
personality Dave Spector and businesswoman Shin Sugok, a third-
generation Korean resident, jointly held a press conference at the
metropolitan government building demanding that Ishihara resign
immediately over the remarks.
</P>
<P>
"Sankokujin" is a Japanese term that literally means "people
from third countries." Referring to people from former Japanese
colonies in Taiwan and the Korean peninsula, as well as their
descendants, the term gained currency after World War II. It is
now widely regarded as a derogatory term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
