<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers in South China Combating Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Local government officials in
the city of Maoming in south China's Guangdong Province have been
mobilizing 250,000 people daily to help combat a serious drought
that hit the region since last year.
</P>
<P>
All sorts of equipment is being used to combat the drought, and
8.6 million yuan has been spent for the effort, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The city had only 77 mm of rainfall in the first three months
this year, which has led to a drastic drop in the volume of water
in local reservoirs, and the drying-up of a great number of small
reservoirs and ponds. As the drought continues, 51,700 hectares of
crops are being affected.
</P>
<P>
However, thanks to these drought-fighting efforts, 22,000
hectares of arable land are now being irrigated, which has
partially paved the way for spring ploughing and sowing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
