<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, Canada Sign Four Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Atef Obeid
and his Canadian counterpart Jean Chretien capped their talks on
Wednesday with the signing of four pacts.
</P>
<P>
Chretien arrived in Cairo Tuesday for a three-day visit to Egypt
as part of a regional tour, which also includes Syria, Lebanon,
Jordan, the Palestinian self-rule areas, Israel and Saudi Arabia.
He went into a session of talks with Obeid Wednesday morning on
regional issues and bilateral economic relations.
</P>
<P>
Under one of the agreements, Canada will grant Egypt 5 million
U.S. dollars for updating its legislations and policies on small-
and medium-sized enterprises, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding called for expansion of
cooperation in technology transfer, environmental protection and
relevant services, with an emphasis on the role played by the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
A protocol is about Egypt's import of potato seeds from Canada.
</P>
<P>
A fourth agreement was signed between Egypt's Ministry of
Housing and Urban Communities and a Canadian company, concerning
117-million-dollar water projects.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the company will run two water plants and
build one plant in the northwest of the Suez Gulf, and build a 132-
kilometer pipeline to channel water from Cairo to Ain Sokhna port
on the Red Sea, which is now under construction.
</P>
<P>
The company was charged with supplying water to the northwest of
the Suez Gulf, which the Egyptian government has selected as the
site of an industrial development zone, over a period of 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Obeid said at the signing ceremony that Egypt will enhance
cooperation with the Canadian postal authority in transferring
technology in postal services.
</P>
<P>
Egypt also seeks closer cooperation with Canada in landmines
removal, higher education and civil aviation, he added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is estimated to have over 17 million landmines in the
Western Desert and the Sinai Desert left over from conflicts in the
World War II and the Arab-Israeli wars. It calls for international
help to remove the mines, which hinder national development.
</P>
</TEXT>
