<HEADLINE> Malaysia Calls Stability Cornerstone of National Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Political, economic and
societal stability forms the cornerstone of Malaysia's national
policy, Malaysian Defense Minister Najib Tun Razak said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has been consistent in its approach toward defense and
development by always placing development as its best and most
effective form of security, Najib said at a seminar on "War, Peace,
Globalization and Asian Security" held in conjunction with the on-
going Defense Services Asia (DSA 2000) Exhibition and Conference
here.
</P>
<P>
"By bringing development and prosperity, we have successfully
averted any real forms of domestic conflict," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia also believes in regional security, and to achieve
that it has maintained a whole array of security and defense
arrangements and mechanisms such as the ASEAN Regional Forum, Five
Powers Defense Arrangement and numerous other bilateral exercises,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have been pragmatic in looking at regional security, for we
have come to adopt an inclusive approach, where we are open to all
forms of cooperation, with any party that shows genuine interest
in forging peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Touching on globalization, the minister said that while global
markets are being opened, local ones could be forced to shut down
and this could have a high social cost, subsequently leading to
domestic instability.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest challenge for all of us is to try and influence
the process of globalization," he said, adding that regionalism is
a viable option when it comes to dealing with the forces of
globalization.
</P>
<P>
He said that in a world of globalization, the line that
separates politics, economics and society and their implications
for security is fast thinning.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, there is a need to seriously consider the prudence
of forming regional multifaceted institutions, which could well
provide the basis for conflict management, conflict prevention and
eventually conflict resolution, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
