<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Oil States Jubilate Over 13 percent Derivation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Jubilating citizens of Nigeria's
oil- producing states Tuesday continued to express gratitude to
President Olusegun Obasanjo for approving the implementation of 13
percent revenue derivation from the oil income.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper Wednesday that some
citizens of the southeastern Akwa Ibom State, where Obasanjo
announced the decision at the weekend said that they were sure
that the long years of neglect of the state by federal government
were over.
</P>
<P>
They were confident that such problems as lack of
infrastructure and other facilities would soon be adequately
addressed with increased money and attention, according to the
paper.
</P>
<P>
According to the new formula, 13 percent of the oil income from
the region will be retained for local use.
</P>
<P>
People in the Rivers and Bayelsa states also expressed support
for the establishment of the Niger Delta Development Commission
(NDDC), which is authorized to pool together the resources at
federal, state levels and by corporate sector to improve the
welfare of people in the oil-producing region.
</P>
<P>
During to long period of neglect by the military regimes often
dominated by the northerners of the country, the oil producing
Niger delta area has become one of the poorest regions in the
Africa's largest oil producing country. Over 90 percent of the
crude oil in Nigeria was produced in the area.
</P>
<P>
More than two thousand People have killed in poverty related
violences in the past two years in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
