<HEADLINE> China, Malaysia Sign WTO agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 12 (Xinhua) -- China and Malaysia Wednesday
signed a bilateral agreement on China's entry into the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Chinese Minister of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation Shi Guangsheng and Malaysian Minister of
International Trade and Industry Paduka Rafidah Aziz.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers said after the signing ceremony that the
bilateral agreement will help expand Sino-Malaysian trade and
promote China's economic and trade relations with ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah said Malaysia has been strongly supporting China's
early admission into the world trade body as it believes that
China, as a major trading nation, should not be left out of the
WTO.
</P>
<P>
She said that Malaysia looks forward to China's accession into
the TWO this year and China's participation by China in the world
trade body will contribute to the strengthening of the
multilateral trading system.
</P>
<P>
WTO members yet to conclude a similar agreement with China
include the European Union, Mexico and Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Before the signing of the deal, the two ministers held talks on
developing trading ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Shi is here also to attend the second ASEAN business summit
being held in Kuala Lumpur, capital of Malaysia. 
</P>
