<HEADLINE> Chirac Meets With U.N. Representative for West Sahara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
held a meeting on Wednesday with James Baker, United Nations
representative for West Sahara and a former U.S. Secretary of
State.
</P>
<P>
No specific points of the talks were released after the meeting
at the Elysee presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
Baker is expected to organize a meeting of all sides involved
in the conflict by the end of May, aimed at breaking the deadlock
of the process in organizing a self-determination referendum in
West Sahara.
</P>
<P>
He said earlier on Wednesday in Madrid, Spain, that the U.N.
peace plan for West Sahara remains alive despite the current
problems.
</P>
<P>
Morocco, which annexed West Sahara in 1975, claims the right to
vote by the Saharans living in Morocco and the Moroccans living in
West Sahara, while the pro-independence Front Polisario wants to
limit the electoral body to the population registered in a census
in 1974 by Spain, the former colonial power there.
</P>
<P>
During his information-collecting tour, Baker has already
visited Spain, Morocco and Algeria, where the headquarters of the
Front Polisario is based.
</P>
<P>
He will fly back to New York on Wednesday to inform UN
Secretary General Kofi Annan of the possibility of organizing a
meeting of all the countries and parties concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
