<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motor Vehicle Theft Gang Busted in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Beijing police recently cracked
the case of a motor vehicle theft ring, the largest one of its
kind since the founding of New China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
The police have detained 26 suspected criminal gang members who
confessed to 206 thefts. The authorities also recovered 36 stolen
vehicles, mobile phones, pagers, and tools used for the thefts.
</P>
<P>
The gang was mainly made up of farmers from Dingxing County in
north China's Hebei province, who stole vehicles in Beijing and
sold them in ten other provinces around the country, said Liu
Qunli, vice director of the Xuanwu branch of the Beijing Public
Security Bureau (BPSB).
</P>
<P>
Liu said that policemen with the Xuanwu branch of the BPSB
interrogated and examined two suspects as they patrolled the
street of Guanganmen in southwestern Beijing in February, and
eventually rounded up the rest of the gang.
</P>
<P>
The police work for this case took more than 40 days.
</P>
<P>
The thieves began stealing vehicles in 1997, mainly targeting
Santana 2000 cars, which are easily sold, and account for more
than 80 percent of the stolen vehicles, said Liu.
</P>
<P>
The suspects were armed with modern communications gadgets such
as mobile phones and pagers, rare in such cases, according to
police.
</P>
<P>
The police reminded Beijing car owners to be even more cautious,
although most cars are equipped with electronic alarm systems to
prevent theft.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
