<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Finance Operates Smoothly in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- China's financial sector has had
normal and smooth operations and shown positive development trend
in the first quarter of this year, according to the latest
financial statistics released today by the People's Bank of China
(PBOC).
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, by the end of March, the
outstanding amount of broad money (currency in circulation plus
corporate deposits and savings deposits) was 12.258 trillion yuan,
up 13 percent from the same 1999 period; the outstanding amount of
narrow money (cash plus demand deposits) was 4.5158 trillion yuan,
up 18.7 percent; and cash in circulation was 1.3235 trillion yuan,
up 16.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the net amount of money withdrawn from circulation
was 22 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March, the outstanding amount of all deposits was
11.232 trillion yuan, up 13 percent. Of which 3.7387 trillion yuan
were corporate deposits, an increase of 17.3 percent, and 6.2492
trillion yuan were residents' deposits, up 8.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the outstanding amount of loans was 9.5776
trillion yuan, up 13.4 percent in constant terms.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March, China's foreign exchange reserves reached
156.82 billion U.S. dollars, increasing 2.15 billion U.S. dollars
over the end of last year, and the exchange rate of the yuan was
one U.S. dollar per 8.2788 yuan, up five basic points from the end
of last year, remaining stable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
