<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Astronomical Center Sets New Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- China's National Astronomical
Observatory Center will give solid support to nine research fields
this century, with research into the large-scale structure of
universe at the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
The other fields involve the formation and evolution of
galaxies, stars, and solar systems, and advanced astronomical
observation techniques, said Ai Guoxiang, head of the observatory
center.
</P>
<P>
The national astronomical observatory center consists of five
observatories in Beijing, Nanjing, Shanghai, and others, and some
observatory stations under the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
The formation of the network is aimed at making better use of
large astronomical equipment and making astronomical resources
available to scientists all across the country.
</P>
<P>
The center will also build the Large Sky Area Multi-Object
Fiber Spectroscopy Telescope (LAMOST), a space solar telescope,
and a large radio telescope, said Professor Ai.
</P>
<P>
The three projects, along with new observatories built in
Yunnan Province, is expected to help astronomical research in
China reach the world's advanced level, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
