<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Canadian PMs Discuss Regional Issues, Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Atef Obeid
held talks Wednesday with his visiting Canadian counterpart Jean
Chretien on regional issues and ways of boosting bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
The talks dealt with the latest developments in the Middle East
peace process, Canada's role in helping push forward the peace
march, and optimal utilization of its expertise in peacekeeping and
mine removal, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Chretien arrived in Cairo Tuesday night for a three-day visit as
part of a regional tour which also includes Syria, Lebanon, Jordan,
the Palestinian self-rule areas, Israel and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Chretien's arrival, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa on Tuesday expressed welcome to his visit, which Moussa said
would further bolster the bilateral ties of cooperation. He said
Egypt highly appreciates Canada's role in international
peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
Obeid and Chretien also discussed bilateral economic ties, ways
of increasing Canadian investments in Egypt and expanding trade,
the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume stood at 176 million U.S. dollars in 1999
between the two countries, decreasing by 8.19 percent from 1998.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Canada seek to boost economic and trade cooperation
through forging a free trade agreement and Canada's contribution to
Egypt's development projects, especially in the field of
infrastructure, irrigation and technology transfer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
