<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Turkish newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- The summit of Turkey's ruling coalition to discuss
presidential candidates, scheduled for Tuesday, was postponed
because Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit got a cold.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the scheduled summit, Ecevit said "there will be a
chaos, unless a common candidate is named."
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that in the coming days, Turkish politics will be
inflicted with the struggle for choice of a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom):
</P>
<P>
-- A Turkish citizen, named Halil Celik who runs a restaurant in
Sheffield, Britain, was assaulted on Tuesday by some British
fanatics in revenge for deaths of two British fans, who were
stabbed by Turkish hooligans in Istanbul last week during the
Galatasaray-Leeds United match.
</P>
<P>
Celik said that just because of his Turkish origin, he was
beaten. In Britain, some radicals threatened to launch an anti-
Turkish citizen campaign.
</P>
<P>
Cumhuriyet (Republic):
</P>
<P>
-- The European Union Commissioner Gunter Verheugen, in charge
of enlargement, said on Tuesday that the existence of Turkish
troops in Cyprus "does not hinder its EU membership," adding the
military presence is an element of peace on the Island.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the Turkey-EU Partnership Council
meeting, which convened in Luxembourg to review Turkey's progress
toward the Copenhagen criteria.
</P>
<P>
The EU said that it appreciates the reforms Turkey has made to
accommodate EU's requirements since Ankara was accepted as a
candidate for a full membership at the EU Helsinki summit last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
