<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Business Summit Concludes in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The second ASEAN Business
Summit concluded here Wednesday with a call for Asia to enunciate
strategies for the working together amongst its constituent
members to counter-balance the globalization.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah
Aziz made the call at the close of the two-day summit with the
theme "Asia 2000: Moving Forward."
</P>
<P>
She said that regionalism can be an effective counter-balance
mechanism for East Asia and Asia in minimizing the impact of
globalization.
</P>
<P>
In regionalism, she said, various economic buffers could be
instituted and regional economic strength be galvanized to face
the challenges of globalization.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian minister said that for Asia to move forward
beyond 2000, the region's political thinking must first move
beyond its present phase of minimum action.
</P>
<P>
"For Asia to move forward as a region successfully, there must
be the strong core of Asians at the political, planning,
management levels to think through and operationalize the Asian
initiatives,"Rafidah said.
</P>
<P>
She said the Asian regional cooperation can only be realized
and be made to work, if there exists the necessary framework for
the process to happen.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed out that priority areas and economic
sectors can be identified and be the bases for economic
collaboration, including the financial and services sectors,
manufacturing and technology.
</P>
<P>
The next process would then begin where Pan-Asian policies and
measures would be evolved and established, allowing for effective
collaboration among private sector entities and result in
corporate mergers and tie-ups within the region, she said.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, the ensuring entities would be able to be global
players and integrate into the globalization process. Domestic
industries that have the capacity and potential could integrate
and synergize to evolve as Asian industries with strong regional
networks and capacity to make an impact in the global market,"
Rafidah said.
</P>
<P>
She suggested that at the next meeting of Asian leaders and of
East Asian leaders special focus be given to concrete areas of
regional cooperation, particularly among trade and industrial
communities.
</P>
<P>
The summit was jointly organized by the National Chamber of
Commerce and Industry of Malaysia and the Asian Strategy
Leadership Institute under the auspices of the ASEAN Chamber of
Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar,the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
Representatives from all ASEAN members except for Cambodia and
Laos attended the summit.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Minister Shi
Guangsheng was invited to address the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
