<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Introduce African Culture Course in Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian will introduce African
culture to its schools' curricula, to stem moral decay in the
country, said the Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted sources in the Presidency as saying that
President Olusegun Obasanjo had approved the teaching of the
subject as part of the new educational policy for both primary and
secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
The subject to be taught under the program is tagged: "Back to
Basic African Culture Knowledge (B.A.C.K)." It is aimed at
acquainting school children with African traditional values as
well as monitoring and selecting foreign cultures to be imbibed by
children.
</P>
<P>
The presidency also expected that the B.A.C.K would also
contribute to the curbing of cultism in the society.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, when fully operational, children
wishing to enter into the university would have to produce
evidence of pass in cultural knowledge before they are granted
admission.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, it was gathered that African proverbs,
history and beliefs and mythology would be inculcated into school
children, aimed at breeding a new generation of Nigerians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
