<HEADLINE> Portugal Bars 12 Angolans from Entering Portugal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Twelve Angolans arriving at the
Lisbon Airport were prohibited from entering Portugal in a
retaliatory move by the Portuguese authorities, official news
agency Angop said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese assistant secretary of state for internal
administration Manuel Diogo, said that the Angolans, whose travel
documents were not in order, would be sent back to Luanda "as soon
as possible".
</P>
<P>
Diogo said the tightened immigration procedures represented "a
new stance" of "greater rigour" on the part of Portugal, which
would continue in response to Angola's recent treatment of
Portuguese travellers arriving in Luanda.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the internal administration ministry announced
late Monday that Portuguese authorities would tighten screening of
Angolans in a tit-for-tat response to Luanda's recent barring of
many Portuguese travellers.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the stiffened immigration controls of
Angolans was based on "the principle of reciprocity".
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, Prime Minister Antonio Guterres said Portugal
would respond with "total firmness" if it were determined that
Angola was acting outside "the good relations" between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic flap broke at the weekend when Angolan
authorities on two occasions barred entry to 27 Portuguese
arriving at Luanda airport. The official explanation was that the
Portuguese travellers were coming to work, but only carrying
tourist visas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
