<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Build Holiday Inn Hotel to Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will help
Tanzania build a high-grade Holiday Inn hotel with a total
investment of 13 million U.S. dollars in a bid to boost tourism,
newspapers here reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director Peter Mwenguo of Tanzanian Tourist Board
(TTB) said Tuesday that a South African hotel group will start the
construction of the 162-room hotel in Dar es Salaam next month.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Southern Sun Hotels, the largest hotel operator
in the continent with a chain of 79 hotels and 13,299 rooms, is
the owner of the project.
</P>
<P>
Its Managing Director Helder Pereira said at a launching
ceremony here that the project is not only of bricks-and-mortar
development but also a catalyst for job creation and skills
development.
</P>
<P>
Pereira said that construction work will support jobs for 400
workers and over 200 hotel staff will be employed in the hotel
which includes 152 rooms, 10 executive rooms and modern
facilities.
</P>
<P>
He said Southern Sun already has a stake in Tanzania's tourist
infrastructure through a strategic investment in several game
lodges and camps.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian authorities said that presently Tanzania has 215
hotels with 7, 500 rooms and 13,400 beds to cater for more than
550,000 tourists visiting its attractions annually.
</P>
<P>
Emmanuel Ole Naikom, director of the Investment Promotion at
the Tanzania Investment Center, said late march that the number of
hotels must be increased to match with the growing number of
tourists.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government will grade hotels in accordance
with international criteria so as to motivate the various hotels
to maintain professional standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
