<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greater Effort Urged to Improve Environment Around Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Greater effort must be made to
improve the environment in areas around the Chinese capital of
Beijing, a senior Beijing official said in a recent interview
with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"This brooks no delay," said Song Xiyou, director of the
Beijing Municipal Afforestation Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Beijing belongs to the zone of continental monsoon climate,
featuring northwester in most cases in spring and autumn, Song
noted.
</P>
<P>
Dust storms that are formed in Beijing's windward areas such as
Hebei and Shanxi provinces, and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region where environmental improvement is relatively slow, still
pose a big threat to the capital's environment, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, what is more important in improving Beijing
's environment is to intensify the effort to improve the
environment in the windward areas of Beijing, and go all out to
plant trees and grass and turn the farmland reclaimed in recent
years into grassland and forests.
</P>
<P>
"It is far from enough to depend only on Beijing to improve its
environment by planting trees and grass," he added.
</P>
<P>
The capital city has been hit by six dust storms since the
beginning of this year and this is the worst case in recent years,
meteorologists say.
</P>
<P>
The worst dust storm several days ago forced 40 flights,
including one from Copenhagen to Beijing to land in the nearby
port city of Tianjin instead. Another 40 flights were unable to
take off due to poor visibility, excluding four flights were
forced to fly back and six canceled.
</P>
<P>
In north Beijing, the density of floating dust in the air in
some cases reached 1,000 mg per sq. m. and the visibility was just
100 to 200 meters, and pedestrians had to put on masks or wrap
their heads with gauze kerchiefs.
</P>
<P>
To do its part, Beijing has started building a 100-sq-km forest
belt around the city, which is scheduled to complete by the year
2002.
</P>
<P>
The central government also has allocated a total of about 120
million yuan (about 15 million U.S. dollars) for the capital city'
s afforestation drive.
</P>
<P>
Now, Beijing's vegetation rate has reached 35.2 percent,
averaging 8.5 sq. m per capita, ranking in the forefront among
major Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
The city will complete a total of 2,100 hectares of vegetation
this year, raising the vegetation rate to 43 percent, which is
equivalent to the total vegetation area completed in the last six
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat Crops Threatened by Disease and Pests in Hebei Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Over 1 million hectares of
wheat fields have been affected by diseases and insect pests in
north China's Hebei Province, one of the country's main gain
producers.
</P>
<P>
Specialists estimate that the affected fields will increase to
1,400,000 ha, accounting for more than half of the province's
wheat fields.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that due to temperature and humidity some diseases
such as blight and wheat aphid were found in February and spread
rampantly in early March.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of disease surpassed 20 percent, and hit 90
percent in some places. Experts predict that some diseases may be
spread more widely.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has taken emergency measures to limit
losses, and related departments are striving to help farmers with
prevention and control of these diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
