<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China to Get More Electricity From West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Along with an ambitious drive to
develop western China, the country is trying to tap the huge power
resources of the region in a bid to provide more electricity for
energy-short eastern China.
</P>
<P>
China's west comprises 10 provinces, autonomous regions, and
one centrally-administered municipality, all very rich in
hydropower resources as well as other renewable energy resources,
said Zhang Guobao, vice-minister in charge of the State
Development Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the just-concluded seminar on transmitting
electricity from west to east, the senior official expects the
recoverable hydropower resources in west China to top 270 million
kw, accounting for about 72 percent of the country's total. In
addition, the region has abundant resources of coal, petroleum,
and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
The official said the strategy of transmitting electricity from
west to east is of significance for improving the country's
energy structure and ecological environment, and is good for the
development of both western and eastern China.
</P>
<P>
Also, it will help reduce environmental pollution and sharply
cut electricity production costs.
</P>
<P>
The official urged provinces and cities in east China to
provide more markets for electricity transmitted from the west by
speeding up the readjustment of energy structure, closing down
small thermal power plants, and prohibiting construction of
conventional coal-fueled thermal plants.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the west should improve its investment environment
in order to attract more funds from outside and optimize power
development plans to ensure a power supply to the east, the
official added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
