<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Prudent on US Firm's DNA Decoding Claim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts involved in
mapping the human genetic code have disputed a private company's
claim that it has already achieved the goal.
</P>
<P>
Celera Genomics, an American company based in the state of
Maryland in the United States, announced last week that it had
finished the decoding phase of one person's genetic code,
according to Science Times.
</P>
<P>
Doctor Zhang Meng of the Human Genome Research Center of the
Chinese Academy of Sciences said that the announcement may only be
of an advertising nature, which could bring more profits to the
company.
</P>
<P>
"A piece of news may mean nothing serious for scientific
research," the paper quoted Shen Yan, a research fellow from the
North China Human Genome Research Center. He said he will not make
any comments until more details are released about the company's
achievement.
</P>
<P>
The company' decoding claim only refers to the first step
toward the final drafting of the human genome map, said Chen
Runsheng, a researcher with the CAS's Institute of Biophysics.
</P>
<P>
He said there is still a major task facing the company, which
is to assemble the genetic fragments to form a complete picture of
the human genome. So far, the announced achievement does not
appear to be very significant, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
