<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Group Demands Review of Sexual Assault Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A women group in Hong Kong has
demanded a review of the sexual assault law because sexual
violence could be happening seven times frequently than the
official figures.
</P>
<P>
In a 35-page action plan issued Tuesday to legislators, the
women group, the Association Concerning Sexual Violence Against
Women, recommended a change to what they called the discriminatory
and outdated definition of rape, which they said failed to count
men as victims or specify martial rape as an offense.
</P>
<P>
The group also recommended the age of a person liable for
prosecution for sexual offenses be lowered from 14 to seven, the
same age applied to other serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
Security Bureau figures put the annual number of reported
indecent assault and rape cases over the past seven years at
between 1,133 and 1,304. But the women group said the official
figures, which suggested there was a sexual attack every sevens
hours, did not give a true picture.
</P>
<P>
The women group's survey found that 85 percent of victims did
not go to the police.  
</P>
</TEXT>
