<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drilon Steps Into Philippine Senate Helm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Senate majority leader
Franklin Drilon assumed the Senate presidency Wednesday afternoon
in place of the outgoing Senate President Blas Ople, the ABS-CBN
news channel reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the presidency turnover ceremony, Drilon said that
as the new Senate chief, he would work hard to help maintain the"
stability of the government."
</P>
<P>
The leadership change is in line with a "gentlemen's agreement"
that Ople and Drilon signed in the presence of President Joseph
Estrada in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Ople, who was elected as Senate president
on July 26 last year, agreed with Drilon to divide between
themselves the remaining two-year tenure following the death of
former Senate President Marcelo Fernan.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada himself brokered the "term-sharing agreement"
as a leadership war threatened to divide the ruling party last
year and impair the government's legislative thrust.
</P>
<P>
Estrada is the titular head of the ruling party LAMP. Both Ople
and Drilon are LAMP's founding members.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the assumption, Drilon told reporters that there
would be no changes in the composition of committee chairmanships,
except for the two key positions, the Senate secretariat and
Commission on Appointment secretary.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Drilon pledged to protect the Senate's integrity as
an independent institution. But he also assured President Estrada
of the passage of his administration's urgent legislative
proposals.
</P>
<P>
Becoming Senate president -- the 7th since 1987 -- is the apex
of Drilon's 14 years of public service since he served in the
former President Corazon Aquino's administration as its deputy
minister for labor.
</P>
<P>
Later, he became Mrs. Aquino's justice secretary and then
executive secretary. In the administration of former President
Fidel Ramos,Drilon also served as justice secretary.
</P>
<P>
Drilon, who earned his law degree in 1969, brought his
expertise in judicial and labor matters when he ran and won a
Senate seat in 1995.
</P>
<P>
He chaired various committees in the 7th Congress, including
the Senate blue ribbon and the committee on bans, financial
institutions and currencies.
</P>
<P>
In the present Congress, Drilon was majority leader. He said it
was during this experience as Senate majority leader that he
aspired for the top Senate post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
