<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Prefers Controlled Inflow of Foreign Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Singapore acting Prime Minister
Lee Hsien Loong Wednesday reaffirmed that his government tries to
manage a controlled inflow of foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 10th Triennial Delegates Conference of the
National Trades Union Congress, Lee made the point to more than 1,
000 delegates to the two-day conference in response to workers'
worries about foreign talents taking top jobs in Singapore and
their greater worries about skilled and semi-skilled foreign
workers competing Singaporeans for jobs.
</P>
<P>
The acting prime minister said the Singapore government
requires local companies to maintain a minimum Singapore to
foreign worker ratio in their employment of workers and uses the
Foreign Worker Levy to moderate demand for foreign workers and to
prevent foreign workers from depressing wages of Singaporeans.
</P>
<P>
The levy is higher for unskilled workers than for skilled
workers because the skilled workers make a greater economic
contribution and the unskilled workers will be paid less, he added.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's total workforce is just over 2 million and of these
Singaporeans account for 1.4 million and foreigners about 600,000.
Companies in this city state employ foreign workers as a measure
to reduce costs because foreign workers are paid much less
compared with Singaporean workers.
</P>
<P>
Last year about 60,000 new jobs were created and more than
three quarters of these were taken by Singaporeans, moving down
the country's unemployment rate to 2.9 percent at the end of 1999
from 4.4 percent at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Lee said, "If we had sent home the 600,000 foreign workers
during the crisis, far from the economy recovering and creating
new jobs, it would have nosedived."
</P>
<P>
"The way to help them (the unemployed workers) is not to keep
out foreign workers, It is to create more new jobs and to prepare
them for the new jobs through training and skills development
programs," the acting prime minister concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
