<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Symposium Focuses on Sending Power From West to East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A symposium focusing on the
transmission of the rich energy resources in western China to the
economically developed east was held in Beijing from April 11 to
12.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Guobao, a vice-minister of the State Development Planning
Commission, said developing rich energy resources in the western
regions and transmitting them to the east is an inevitable choice
for China and a win-win strategy for both the western and eastern
regions.
</P>
<P>
China has potential hydropower resources of 378 million
kilowatts in installed capacity. However, 70 percent of the
resources are in the remote western regions.
</P>
<P>
China has already three major areas through which power in the
west is transmitted to the east. In the north, power is
transmitted from Shanxi and Inner Mongolia to Beijing, Tianjin and
Tangshan. In the south, electricity is transmitted from Guizhou to
Guangdong province and electricity produced by the Gezhouba Power
Station in Hubei Province is transmitted to Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials and top legislators have recently called for
greater efforts to develop hydropower in the west and transmit
such power to the east.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the symposium suggested that the government
should accelerate reforms of the electricity administration system
and optimize the distribution of electricity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners Find Nice Home in Pudong (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
His wife, Bonnie, works for "Shanghai Sunrise", a charity
program to assist local primary and high school students from poor
families, with donations from foreigners working in Shanghai.
Bonnie works very hard, though she gets no pay.
</P>
<P>
Toru Mitarai, president of the Sanwa Bank Shanghai Branch, has
worked in Pudong for seven years. "When I just arrived here, there
were no skyscrapers in Pudong, but the Lujiazui Financial Trade
Zone looks no different to Tokyo and Manhatten."
</P>
<P>
The Japanese banker is deeply impressed with the Chinese
government's efforts to open up the financial sector as Sanwa is
among the first foreign banks allowed to handle RMB businesses
three years ago. "The huge potential for development is the
biggest attraction of Pudong for foreigners," he said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the local government has tried hard to improve
living and working conditions for foreigners.
</P>
<P>
A number of public facilities including schools and a special
clinics for foreign residents have been set up in Pudong. Some
maids working at foreign homes have also been given special
training.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the No.2 Subway and a golf course are
expected to provide more conveniences for foreigners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
