<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas are preparing the ground in
Lebanese refugee camps for Palestinian terrorist groups to attack
Israel, a senior IDF intelligence officer told the Knesset
(parliament) Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah is not just working with religious fundamentalists,
but has established several new secular groups among the 300,000
Palestinian refugees, the officer said.
</P>
<P>
The officer also expressed concern about recent statements by
Syria, some Lebanese government officials and Hezbollah concerning
a potential increase in violence along Israel's northern border.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- By mid-2000, there will be some 3.2 million Palestinians with
53 percent of them under the age of 18, according to a report
issued by the Palestinian National Authority's Central Bureau of
Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Of the estimated 3.2 million Palestinians, 63 percent live in
Gaza and 36.1 percent in the West Bank, said Hassan Libedh, chief
of the Palestinian CBS.
</P>
<P>
Some 37.2 percent of Gaza children and 16.1 percent of West Bank
children live in poverty, it added. The situation in refugee camps
is particularly difficult, with some 37.3 percent of the children
there living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- United States President Bill Clinton Tuesday welcomed Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's plan to pull Israeli troops out of
southern Lebanon this July, and urged him to make faster headway
with the Palestinians on a West Bank withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said Tuesday night that the outlook for success on the
Israeli-Syrian peace track is "no bleaker" than it was before his
failed Geneva summit with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad last
month, but here is "a lot more hope for rapid movement" on the
Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
Barak, in Washington on a fast-paced 18-hour visit, met with U.
S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and U.S. Mideast Special
Envoy Dennis Ross before heading into a meeting with President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Tuesday sent a special
message from Washington to American scholar Deborah Lipstadt, who
was vindicated in a libel suit brought against her in a London
Court by controversial historian David Iving.
</P>
<P>
Writing in the "name of the Israeli people and the Jewish
people," Barak told Lipstadt that her struggle and victory is a
triumph for free people against "dark forces which want humanity's
lowest point to be forgotten."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the British High Court exonerated Lipstadt, professor
of history at Emory University in Atlanta, Georgia, of all the main
charges stemming from her 1994 book, Denying the Holocaust: the
Growing Assault on Truth and Memory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
