<HEADLINE> Share Prices Surge in Tokyo, Nikkei Hits 40-Month Closing High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose sharply in Tokyo
Wednesday on the back of gains in domestic demand-related issues,
with the benchmark Nikkei index hitting a 40-month closing high.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange surged 310.69 points, or 1.51
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 20,833.21, the highest
close since December 5, 1996, when it finished at 20,943.90.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, added 5.25 points, or 0.31 percent, to 1,706.
34.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 682.13 million
shares from Tuesday's 586.82 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
After opening, the Nikkei rose on gains made by domestically
oriented issues following an improved economic assessment issued
by the Bank of Japan (BOJ), traders said.
</P>
<P>
Real estate firms, banks attracted active buying, while
warehousing firms, construction firms and nonlife insurers saw
large gains.
</P>
<P>
However, uncertainty over the course of high-tech issues in New
York dampened information and technology issues in Tokyo, traders
said.
</P>
<P>
Brokerage houses, wholesalers and nonferrous metal makers also
faced selling, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outnumbered
losers 790 to 483, with 119 issues closing unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
