<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Reduces Toll Gates on Highways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 12 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang Province
has abolished 21 toll gates on its highways so far this year as
part of a national drive to end illegal highways charges.
</P>
<P>
The toll gates were set up on national highways No.104 and No.
302, accounting for about 20 percent of Zhejiang's total, and
doing away with them will save more than 200 million yuan (24
million US dollars) in fees for vehicles passing along the
highways annually, according to local transport authorities.
</P>
<P>
The highways are now operating smoothly without the toll gates,
they said.
</P>
<P>
The province has since 1992 invested a total of 38.8 billion
yuan, which would be used to rebuild and upgrade 3,447 kilometers
of highways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
