<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumers Warned of Tourism Scams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The China Consumers' Association
(CCA) has offered tips to tourists on choosing travel agencies to
help prevent agency scams, according to today's "Economic Daily".
</P>
<P>
The CAA has advised consumers to choose reputable and
registered travel agencies. "China has more than 1,000 tourist
agencies and only 67 of them are officially approved to offer
services for overseas tour groups," said an official with CCA.
</P>
<P>
Representative offices of registered travel agencies in China
are not allowed to organize or receive travel groups, he added.
</P>
<P>
Cheap tour packages offered by some small travel agencies only
charge travel expenses and entrance fees to scenic spots. These
seemingly attractive offers turn out to be scams when tour groups
organized by some agencies take tourists to over-priced gift
stores and make a commission from sales, the official warned.
</P>
<P>
Consumers are also advised to carefully study contracts they
sign with travel agencies and buy travel insurance.
</P>
<P>
CCA handled some 5,330 complaints about travel agencies last
year, up 41 percent from the previous year. The majority of
complaints involved tours to Hong Kong, Singapore, Malaysia and
Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
