<HEADLINE> 1st Temporary Storage for Nuclear Waste Set up in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- China has recently set up its
first advanced temporary storage for nuclear wastes discharged
from civilian-use reactors in southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The storage is built by the Nuclear Power Research and Design
Institute of China to hold solid nuclear waste and other
radioactive waste materials. Some of the waste will be disposed of
permanently by burying it deep underground, an official with the
State Environmental Protection Administration of China (SEPA) said
today.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear waste storage will be capable of handling and
disposing 1,000 barrels of nuclear waste each year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there are a total of 27 smaller temporary storage
facilities in major cities across China for discarded radioactive
wastes, which are discharged from hospitals and other medical
institutions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
