<HEADLINE> Teenagers Deliver Science Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- "The title of our report is '
analysis of the regulating effect of the coliform bacteria HU
albumen at the beginning of duplication process of bacteriophage
DNA'," 13-year-old Chen Xiaoyan told more than 100 listeners, and
could not conceal his childishness.
</P>
<P>
Chen and Fang Zhou, co-author of the report attended a
scientific seminar for youngsters in Beijing last weekend. The
seminar, sponsored by the Chinese Association for Science and
Technology (CAST), drew students from 12 middle schools.
</P>
<P>
With the help of CAST, Chen and Fang started their research in
the Institute of Microbiology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (
CAS) last year.
</P>
<P>
Other lecturers explained their studies in basic research
fields including biotherapy on tumors, trans-genic animals, and
control of blue algae pollution.
</P>
<P>
Besides these abstruse reports, some students expanded their
research from sex education among youngsters to nutrition among
Chinese schoolchildren, which were more understandable to the
student listeners.
</P>
<P>
During the discussion period after every report, boys and girls
would raise some pointless questions, and the young lecturers
answered them nervously.
</P>
<P>
An organizer of the seminar from CAST said, "We select some
middle school students with high interest in science and help them
do research in their spare time in the institutes and labs of CAS
or Beijing University or Qinghua University."
</P>
<P>
"It is part of our plan to train talent in the life sciences,
and the training will be expanded to other research fields in the
future," he said.
</P>
<P>
The most outstanding reports selected by experts will be
submitted to the national science and technology innovation
contest for youngsters, which is expected to be held in east China
's Anhui Province in August.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Zengyi, an official with the Ministry of Education, said
scientific research classes will be set up in the high schools in
some provinces this autumn to stimulate student interest in
science. 
</P>
</TEXT>
