<HEADLINE> Foreigners Find Nice Home in Pudong (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- "In the beginning, it was merely
a house, but now it is our home," Francisco Guerra says, sitting
in his residence in the Pudong New Area, Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
To work in China had been a dream for this Philippine man who
is now vice chairman of the S.C. Johnson and Son, Inc., USA and
executive chairman of Shanghai Johnson Ltd..
</P>
<P>
Like many of the 25,000 foreign nationals working in Pudong, Mr.
Guerra and his family have found a comfortable home in this 10-
year old development zone, since they sold their old house in the
United States four years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Even my son often tells his classmates he is Shanghainese,"
says the father. His son is studying at the Shanghai American
School in Pudong.
</P>
<P>
Marketing in China is somewhat harder than he thought, but Mr.
Guerra says he likes China best. His Chinese colleagues call him "
Gaile", which sounds like "great" in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Guerra is fond of reading and swimming in his spare time.
Sometimes, the couple take a stroll along commercial streets,
local markets that sells flowers and birds, or some other places
of interests in Pudong. "Nobody knows we are foreigners until we
open our mouth," says the husband.
</P>
