<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Grant Amnesty to 12,500 Prisoners in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's public security
department is considering a list of over 12,500 prisoners for the
first batch of the special amnesty in 2000, Vietnam News Agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Central Advisory Council for Special Amnesties (CACSA) of
the country said a list of eligible inmates will be sent to State
President Tran Duc Luong for endorsement.
</P>
<P>
The prisoners will be released on the occasion of the 25th
anniversary of the country's liberation of the South and national
reunification (April 30),
</P>
<P>
According to Pham Duc Chan, Deputy Director of the Department
for Detention Camp Management under the Ministry of Public
Security, his department had received by April 11 nearly 13,000
applications for early release by prisoners from detention camps
throughout the country without any complaint about amnesty
considerations by detention camps' officials.
</P>
<P>
He added that nine inter-branch expert groups under the CACSA
began examining the records of prisoners proposed for special
amnesty in nine regions across the country on March 17, nearly one
month after President Tran Duc Luong signed Decision on special
amnesty in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Over 500 of 13,000 amnesty applicants failed to meet the
required conditions, Chan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
