<HEADLINE> Kenya to Sell Telecommunication Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government will sell
49 percent stake in the Telkom Kenya Company which operates the
country's telecommunication infrastructure, Kenyan Finance
Minister Chris Okemo has said.
</P>
<P>
The privatization process of the company was launched Tuesday
in the capital Nairobi in the presence of leading industrialists
and members of diplomatic corps, newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Okemo said all interested parties are to be invited by an
official tender in domestic and international press including the
international edition of the Financial Times and the Wall Street
Journal.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the tender will be simultaneously mailed to 20 top
 international telecommunication companies who are believed to be
interested in the biding process, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Okemo, the process based on a strict criterion
which stipulates that a bidder be a telecommunication company
which operates a network of over 500,000 fixed lines, demonstrates
financial stability supported by audited annual account and has a
minimum of two years of operating history.
</P>
<P>
Okemo said by September 30, this year, an agreement will be
reached with the strategic partner based on the price offered, the
timing of investment in Telkom Kenya, proposed level of management
involvement and the business plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
