<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty Eradication Remains Tanzania's Long-term Goal: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A Tanzanian government
official has said that poverty eradication was still a long
standing goal in the country despite the debt relief.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the Guardian newspaper on Wednesday,
the government has told donor countries that a two billion U.S.
dollar debt relief for Tanzania under the Highly Indebted Poor
Countries (HIPC) initiative was still not enough to free the
cash-strapped country from the shackles of poverty.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister of State in the Vice-President's Office
Edward Lowassa urged the donor community to cancel all debts
outright, reduce conditions attached to aid and review the
practice of restricting aid.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who is in charge of poverty alleviation issues,
made the remarks while speaking to visiting ministers for
International Development from Germany, the Netherlands, Norway
and Britain on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
More was still needed to be done to promote broad-based growth
in the country where half of the population are still living below
the poverty line of the 0.65 U.S. dollar daily income.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and the International Monetary Fund announced
last week that they will halve Tanzania's debt servicing bill for
2001-2003 and reduce it by a third in future years.
</P>
<P>
They pledged that it will create room for additional
expenditures on poverty reduction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
