<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Police Find Cult Witnesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan police have located
several witnesses who stayed at the Kanungu cult camp in the
southwestern Uganda on the eve of March 17 when over 500 cult
members were burnt to death, the New Vision daily reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After a three-week investigation, the police found that several
taxi operators had ferried hundreds of people to Kanungu from
different parts of the east African country, the newspaper quoted
Terence Kinyera, chief of criminal investigation department of the
southwestern region, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kinyera said that one of the witnesses was a driver from
Mbarara town, who ferried a family of nine to Kanungu on March 16
and was hosted at the camp for the night.
</P>
<P>
Several local residents have indicated in separate interviews
that the Kanungu victims were ferried from different cult
locations by hired vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Residents in the area where the police exhumed 81 bodies from a
mass grave last week said that the cult members were ferried
aboard a green Dyna pick-up truck on March 15.
</P>
<P>
The police have identified the vehicle and its driver from
Kabira in Bushenyi, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted a police source as saying that the cult
leaders sent out several messages to all their former members who
had defected, imploring them to join the cult for celebrations and
thanksgiving ceremonies, but they turned down invitations to
return to the cult.
</P>
<P>
The police sources were quoted as saying that they had
recovered invitation letters issued by the cult leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
