<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, April 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Russian President Vladimir Putin will make an
official visit to the United Kingdom on coming Sunday, a spokesman
for Downing Street said.
</P>
<P>
Putin is expected to fly into London late on Sunday night for
talks with Prime Minister Tony Blair. The spokesman also confirmed
that Britain was "still under active discussion" with Russia on a
possible meeting between Putin and Queen Elizabeth II. (Russia-UK-
Putin-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak won the support
for a planned Israeli troop pull out of southern Lebanon from the
Clinton administration when he held talks with the U.S. Secretary
of State on Tuesday, but he was also pressed to move fast on the
Israeli-Palestinian track in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright praised Barak at a news conference for planning to
pull Israeli troops out of southern Lebanon in July under U.N.
resolutions. Albright also pressed Barak to move as fast as
possible with the Palestinians toward a West Bank withdrawal. (US-
Israel-Pullback)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuelan Energy Minister Ali Rodriguez said on
Tuesday that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (
OPEC) will review the effects of the oil output increase decided
by the organization in March.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC ministers will hold an extraordinary meeting on June
21 in Vienna "to make a balance of the decisions taken in relation
to production, and the market will be analyzed to know its
performance," said Rodriguez in a communique of the Venezuelan
Ministry of Energy. (Venezuela-OPEC-Oil)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- Peru's presidential candidate Alejandro Toledo warned
Tuesday that the opposition parties won't accept any result from
the National Organization of Electoral Processes (NOEP) declaring
President Alberto Fujimori the winner.
</P>
<P>
He also indicated the parties won't make concessions on their
democratic rights. Official statistics showed Tuesday that with 90.
82 percent of the ballots counted, Fujimori had won 49.79 percent,
compared to Toledo's 40.39 percent. The parties accused NOEP of
manipulating the elections to make Fujimori the absolute winner. (
Peru-Election-Fujimori)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Former chief of the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI)
Soerjadi was arrested over his alleged involvement in a bloodshed
in July 1996, local leading newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Soerjadi, who is also a member of the Supreme Advisory Council,
was interrogated by the police for 10 hours on Tuesday. Meanwhile,
former Minister of Home Affairs Syarwan Hamid is expected to be
questioned too, over his alleged role in the same incident which
sparked by a forcible takeover of the party's headquarters in July
27, 1996. (Indonesia-Chief Arrested) 
</P>
