<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coordinated Efforts Protect Cultural Relics in Western China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The provinces and autonomous
regions of western China are making coordinated effort to protect
their cultural relics during the anticipated development of the
west.
</P>
<P>
The newly founded Shaanxi Provincial Leading Group for
Development of Western China, for example, consists of experts on
local cultural relics who are conducting archaeological
excavations before the construction of roads and railways begins.
</P>
<P>
Western China, the cradle of Chinese civilization, makes up 56.
8 percent of the country's total area. The region is rich in
cultural relics, including terra-cotta warriors and the Mausoleum
of Emperor Qin Shihuang, the first emperor of the Qin Dynasty (221-
206 B.C.) in Shaanxi, the Mogao Grottoes in Gansu, and the Dazu (
Big Foot) Rock Carvings in Sichuan, all of which are cited on the
World Cultural Heritage list.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wenbin, director of the State Bureau of Cultural Relics,
recently said the bureau has made the protection of cultural
relics a part of the overall development plan for western China.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang Ugyur Autonomous Region intends to focus on the
protection of the ancient Silk Road and mummified bodies, whereas
Guizhou Province in southwest China will protect its 24 unique
ethnic villages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Hold Forum on Ecological Agriculture in Western China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As part of International High-Technology Industries Week 2000,
the forum aims to publicize technological achievements and
opportunities for investment in high and new technology industries
as part of the strategy to develop the country's western region.
</P>
<P>
Forum topics will include the central government's policies on
the development of the west, technology for developing ecological
agriculture, the WTO and ecological agriculture, and the
ecological environment of the west.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Baorui, the official in charge of Beijing's high-tech
industries groups, said the forum will also involve some specific
subjects on ecological agriculture, including high-quality crops,
new species for animal husbandry, sustained development of
grassland livestock, water-saving farming and farm produce
processing, agricultural information networking and data banks,
agro-biological technology, and remote sensing technology.
</P>
