<HEADLINE> World Community Urged to Offer Emergency Relief Food to Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of United
Nations bodies in Ethiopia have appealed to the international
community to step up food aid to drought affected people in the
Horn of Africa country.
</P>
<P>
The representatives from the World Food Program (WFP), the
World health Organization (WHO), The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF), the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), and
the World Bank made the appeal on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the relief food offered so far by the international
 community was not adequate, the representatives said that the
world community should continue food assistance to stem the famine
in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
WHO country representative Michel Janclos said although WHO has
 distributed food among the drought-affected people, the supplies
were not sufficient compared with the gravity of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF representative said the body has appealed for 7.7
million U.S. dollars to provide clean water as well as health and
emergency education services to the drought afflicted people.
</P>
<P>
However, UNICEF has received to date only 500,000 U.S. dollars,
 according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Large part of Ethiopia has been reportedly suffering from
drought since late last year with more than eight million people
facing starvation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
