<HEADLINE> Olympic Regatta Course Laden with Weeds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Despite a massive cleanup
campaign by the Olympic Coordination Authority (OCA), the rowing
and kayaking venue for the Sydney Olympic Games was still laden
with weeds and unfit for competition, Australian rowing coach
Brian Richardson said in Sydney on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Working under floodlights, OCA staff had trolled the regatta
center at Penrith scraping weeds off the course in the buildup to
heats of the national selection trials Wednesday but competitors
still complained about being hindered by weeds.
</P>
<P>
On assurances from the OCA that a new harvester combined with a
special herbicide would ensure weeds were eradicated, Canoeing
officials agreed to return the kayak trials to Penrith later this
month.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said the situation had improved in the last week but
the problem had not been solved.
</P>
<P>
An OCA spokesman said aquatic plants in the lake system would
also continue to be closely monitored and, if necessary, cleared.
</P>
</TEXT>
