<HEADLINE> Artificially Fertilized Triplets Thriving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Doctors have confirmed that the
ten-month-old triplets in east China's Jiangsu Province, the
country's first triplets born of artificial fertilization, are
growing healthily.
</P>
<P>
The triplets, one boy and two girls, were born in Shanghai's
Changzheng Hospital on May 13 last year, and they weighed 2,600
grams, 2,100 grams and 2,150 grams at birth.
</P>
<P>
Their parents are a couple from neighboring Jiangsu Province
who both suffered from infertility conditions, and were
successfully treated at the hospital in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 10 to 15 percent of Chinese couples of child-
bearing age suffer from sterility in various forms.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at the Changzheng Hospital have adopted a series of
procedures to help sterile couples have children, including
optimizing sperms outside body and a technique for activating the
sperms, as well as stimulating ovulation and artificial
fertilization inside the uterus.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the hospital say that 34 percent of all sterile
couples who receive artificial fertilization there have had
children.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
