<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Trade Gap Widens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's trade deficit during
July 1999-March 2000 stood at 1.3 billion U.S. dollars, marking a
38.4 percent increase over the same period of last year, the
latest monthly report of the Federal Bureau of Statistics said.
</P>
<P>
The provisional exports during the nine months totaled 320.66
billion rupees, 13.09 percent over the 283.54 billion rupees in
the same period of last year. In dollar term, the exports
registered a 8.91 percent increase from 5.69 billion dollars to 6.
179 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, Pakistan's imports during July 1999-March 2000 totaled
387.939 billion rupees against 324.359 billion rupees during the
same period of the previous year, showing an increase of 19.6
percent. In dollar term, the figures are 7.498 billion dollars
against 6.63 billion dollars, showing an increase of 13.09 percent.
</P>
<P>
In March the country's exports amounted to 35.576 billion
rupees compared with 38.586 billion rupees in February, showing a
decrease of 7.8 percent over February this year, but indicating an
increase of 3.36 percent over March last year. In dollar term, the
exports in March decreased by 7.79 percent to 686.915 million
dollars when compared with February's 744.966 million dollars and
by 0.34 percent compared with March 1999.
</P>
<P>
Imports into Pakistan during March amounted to 46.709 billion
rupees as against 42.354 billion rupees in February 2000 and 39.
214 billion rupees in March of last year, showing an increase of
10.28 percent and 19.11, percent respectively. In dollar term, the
figures are 901.871 million dollars against 817.703 million
dollars and 797.63 million dollars,showing an increase of 10.29
percent and 13.07 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Bureau of Statistics, however, did not give the
reasons for the increase of the trade deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
