<HEADLINE> Uganda Blames Slow-Moving Agriculture for Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has said that poverty in his country is largely caused by the fact
that the largest part of the population are engaged in agriculture
whose progress is slow.
</P>
<P>
He made the comments while addressing a public rally in Luweero
in central Uganda on Tuesday, according to a press release
available here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The president assured those present at the rally that his
ruling National Resistance Movement is trying to tackle the
problems facing the country and will meet the remaining challenges
with vigor and courage.
</P>
<P>
Modernization of agriculture and industrial development were
ways the government has found to lead the country out of poverty,
Museveni added.
</P>
<P>
More than 46 percent of the population in the east African
country are still living under the poverty line and over 80
percent of the Ugandan people are farmers. Poor infrastructure
and unpredictable weather changes are very often blamed for the
prevailing poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
