<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Trade Deficit Increases Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 12 (Xinhua) - Sri Lanka's trade deficit widened
to some 300 million U.S. dollars in the first two months of this
year, an 117 percent increase over the same period a year earlier,
the Central Bank said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in its weekly economic report that the ever-
increasing deficit was due to a sharp surge in imports, including
the importation of aircraft and intermediate goods.
</P>
<P>
Exports grew by 14.7 percent in the January-February 2000
period to 758.6 million dollars from 661.6 million dollars in the
same period of 1999, it said. However, imports were up 32.4
percent at 1.059 billion dollars during the period, it added.
</P>
<P>
The bank said agricultural exports increased by 14.1 percent to
153.5 million dollars from 134.5 million dollars in the first two
months of 1999. Industrial exports, especially those of food and
beverage and petroleum products, were up 15.2 percent at 580.5
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The rise in imports was reflected mainly in two of the three
main categories -- consumer goods, intermediate goods and
investment goods, with imports rising by 4.8 percent, 35.5 percent
and 49.3 percent, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
