<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Has Highest Hepatitis B Rate in Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has been singled out as the
country in southeast Asia having the highest rate of hepatitis B
virus among normal population and pregnant women, local English
daily Vietnam News reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The findings were revealed at a two-day symposium on Hepato-
Biliary diseases held in Hanoi last weekend.
</P>
<P>
The nearly 400 participants coming from Vietnam and other Asia-
Pacific countries including Japan, Thailand, Singapore and
Australia, heard about 40 reports on the prevalence of B, C and G
hepatitis virus; and new therapies for chronic viral hepatitis B
infection, diagnosis and treatment of ascites.
</P>
<P>
A survey showed that of the 53,010 RIA (Radioimmunoassay for
Diagnosis of Viral Hepatitis) tests performed in Vietnam, 45,210
cases were regarded as HBsAg (have been infected with hepatitis B
virus).
</P>
<P>
Prevalence rate of hepatitis B virus among normal Vietnamese
population was estimated at 11 percent; pregnant women, 10,6
percent;patients with hepatitis, 37 percent; liver cancer, 66.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Primary liver cancer is a leading cancer in Vietnam mostly due
to viral B hepatitis, environmental pollution and food
contamination of aflatoxin, said a Vietnamese doctor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
