<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, April 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA -- Jordan became the 136th member of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) on April 11, the trade body announced here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This is truly a historical moment for Jordan, as we have long
aspired to become a member of the WTO," said R.M. Halaiqah, chief
negotiator and secretary general of the Ministry of Industry and
Trade of Jordan at the WTO's General Council meeting. "This is a
turning point in the continued development of the Jordanian
economy." (WTO-Jordan-New Member)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Union (EU) on Tuesday forecast an
economic growth of 3.4 percent for this year and 3.1 percent for
next year.
</P>
<P>
The growth of the gross domestic product for 2000 is estimated
at 3.4 percent for both the 15-nation EU and the 11-nation euro
zone, according to the forecast. (EU-Economy-Growth)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- Singapore Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew Tuesday
stressed the need for East Asian countries to develop a congruence
between laws and rules governing trade and investment so as to
ensure stability, predictability and low transaction costs in
economic activities.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Millennium Law Conference gala dinner hosted by
Singapore Academy of Law, Lee said, "To maximize growth potential,
East Asian countries need to harmonize those parts of their legal
systems that concern cross-border trade." (Singapore-Trade-Law)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's current account surplus in February surged 33.
3 percent from a year earlier to 1,473.7 billion yen (13.5 billion
U.S. dollars), registering the first rise in 13 months, the
Finance Ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The upsurge in the current account surplus came as a climb in
exports outweighed an increase in imports, the ministry said in a
preliminary report. (Japan-Surplus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysia's exports this year are expected to
enjoy continued growth but at a slower pace, International Trade
and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This was due to the economic slow down of the country's biggest
market, the United States, which maintained a share of 21.9
percent of Malaysia's exports with 70.4 billion ringgit (18.526
billion U.S. dollars) in 1999, the minister said at her ministry's
annual trade and industry dialogue with Electrical and electronic
(E&AMP;E) associations and wood-based industry associations here. (
Malaysia-Exports)
</P>
