<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Higher World Cereal Output Forecasted in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 12 (Xinhua) -- World cereal production this year
is predicted higher to 1890 million tonnes, some 1 percent above
1999, according to a report of the Food and Agriculture
Organization of the United Nations (FAO) reaching Xinhua News
Agency Bangkok Bureau Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report forecasts that output of wheat in the world this
year is going to reach 595 million tonnes, 1 percent up from last
year, while that of coarse grains will rise nearly 3 percent to
900 million tonnes. The rice crop (milled-based) is tentatively
forecasted to fall by 1 percent to 395 million tonnes.
</P>
<P>
The FAO's latest forecast of world cereal trade in 1999-2000
period is 222 million tonnes, some 4 percent above the previous
year's volume.
</P>
<P>
While early forecasts predict to higher cereal output in 2000,
the report warned that the production will not be sufficient to
meet expected demands during 2000-2001 period, and may result in
the shrinking of global cereal reserves.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that food emergencies will persist in 34
countries around the world, and unfavorable prospects in several
other countries could lead to localized food supply difficulties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Tech-Share Tumble Not to Derail Asia's Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The recent plunge of U.S.
technology stocks has prompted sharp declines in Asia's tech-
shares in the past weeks, but the volatile New Economy stocks are
unlikely to derail Asia's economic recovery process.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, although Dow Jones industrial average advanced, the
Nasdaq composite index tumbled for the second consecutive day by
132.30 to 4,055.90, following a fall of 258.25 points Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq index is now lower for the year and is nearly 20
percent below its record closing high of 5,048.62 points on March
10.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of Nasdaq's 5.8 percent plunge Monday, Seoul took
one of the hardest hits Tuesday, with the 8.1 percent drop on the
tech-heavy Kosdaq Index. Hong Kong suffered as well, with the Hang
Seng Index dropping 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's selling focused on technology stocks. Internet
investor Hikari Tsushin tumbled 6.6 percent in Tokyo, South Korean
telephone-service provider Dacom sunk 8.3 percent, and China
Telecom fell 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Over the past month, Hong Kong's top Internet stock, Pacific
Century Cyber-Works Ltd, is down 33 percent, while Hikari Tsushin
Inc., a Japanese Internet incubator, is more than 60 percent lower
on the Tokyo exchange.
</P>
<P>
The continuos fall in New Economy stocks has raised the
question:Do the volatile tech-stocks affect Asia's economic
recovery process?
</P>
<P>
Analysts said if tech-shares in the United States and Asia
tumble further, Asia's recovery process could slow down with
weaker consumer confidence, which may affect Asia's exports to the
United States and touch off a possible pullback of new equity
capital in the region.
</P>
<P>
However, the process is unlikely to be derailed because the
region's economic fundamentals remain sound, they said.
</P>
<P>
"A bursting of the (tech-stock) bubble might impact the rate of
growth, but it probably wouldn't push growth into negative
territory,"said Tim Condon, chief regional economist for ING
Barings.
</P>
<P>
The United States is a big market for Asian products. The
possible reduction in U.S. imports from Asia due to lower consumer
confidence will definitely have an impact on the region' economy.
</P>
<P>
But, since intraregional trade accounts for about two-thirds of
Asia's exports, the region's trade will not collapse because of
less imports by the United States. In recent months, most Asian
countries have increased their exports and imports with the
quicker pace of economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
In February, South Korea's customs-cleared exports rose 37
percent while imports rose 58 percent, reflecting improved
business and consumer sentiment in the country. Even in Indonesia,
February exports grew 44.3 percent from a year ago, while imports
increased 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
As the main engine of the region's economic development, Asia's
export growth, and the intraregional trade in particular, would
help the recovery process continue, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, except South Korea, Japan and Hong Kong, New Economy
in other Asian economies is still at the stage of evolution. Asia'
s limited exposure to the Internet games will prevent the region
from being hit hard by a potential bursting of the bubble in the
Internet and technology shares.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the recent tumble in tech-shares is just "a correction,
"and might not continue for too long and affect the region's
recovery,experts said.
</P>
<P>
For the last year and a half, the stock market has become a
market of extremes: extremely high valuations for the New Economy
and extremely low valuations for the Old Economy -- the
traditional sectors,economists said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, they said, the market has tried to correct those
extremes in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
"This is a transitional period when investors are looking for
value and trying to reduce some of their exposure to the
technology sector or to New Economy stocks," said Terrence Alford,
fund manager for Dresdner RCM Global Investors.
</P>
<P>
"But as we move into the latter part of the second quarter and
into the third quarter, investors will focus on the technology (
again)," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
