<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Import Ban on Three-Wheelers Proposed in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Environment and
Forest has proposed a total ban on the import of three-wheel motor
vehicles having two-stroke engines to check the air pollution in
Dhaka and other cities, The Independent newspaper reported here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to the National Board of Revenue (NBR) Tuesday,
the ministry made an alternative proposal to impose a 300 percent
duty on such vehicles to discourage the import. The present duty
on two-stroke engine vehicles is 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also proposed a similar ban on the import of motor
vehicles having four-stroke diesel engines or imposition of 300
present duty since these vehicles are equally responsible for the
air pollution in the city.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, the ministry proposed zero tariff on import of
motor vehicles operated by compressed natural gas which are
environment-friendly.
</P>
<P>
The ministry maintained that the ban on import of leaded fuel
should remain since the measure proved helpful in improving the
environmental condition.
</P>
<P>
Petrol-driven motor cars to be imported in the future must have
catalytic converters to keep the air free from any kind of
pollution,the letter said.
</P>
<P>
Environment Secretary Syed Marghub Murshid who signed the
letter said that inclusion of these measures in the next year's
budget would help improve the environment of the country to a
large extent.
</P>
<P>
He requested the Chairman of NBR to consider the proposals
while preparing the budget for the coming fiscal 2000-2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
