<HEADLINE> Indonesia, UNPKF Sign MOU on Security in Border  Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding (MOU) on how to handle incidents
in the border regions and the repatriation of East Timorese
refugees was signed on Tuesday in Dili, capital of East Timor by
the Udayana Military Commander Maj. Gen. Kiki Syahnakri and UNPKF
Chief Let. Gen.Jaime S De Los Santos, Antara news agency said.
</P>
<P>
It said that both sides considered the agreement as a
significant step forward for the efforts of both sides for
cooperation in maintaining security in the borders regions.
</P>
<P>
"With the signing of the MOU, I hope as of now, every problem
in the border regions could be solved by me and general Santos.
There is no need to politize such a problem," Syahnakri was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Transitional Authority in East Timor (UNTAET)
led by Peter Galbraith has recently voiced their disappointment to
Indonesian Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab and Minister of Defense
Juwono Sudarsono in Jakarta over 16 incidents in the border line,
including the intrusion of villagers into East Timor.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the TNI has since October 1999 noted the
occurrence of 25 cases of incidents in the border regions
including 17 defence and security cases.
</P>
<P>
Over 200,000 East Timorese became refugees in East Nusa
Tenggara following violence in East Timor after the overwhelming
vote for independence during the U.N.-sponsored ballot on August
30 last year.While more than 100,000 East Timorese have been
repatriated in recent months, but around 140,000 others still
remain in refugee camps in the western half of the Timor island
because they have no home or job to return to. 
</P>
