<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Former PDI Chief Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Former chief of the Indonesian
Democratic Party (PDI) Soerjadi was arrested over his alleged
involvement in a bloodshed in July 1996, local leading newspapers
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Soerjadi, who is also a member of the Supreme Advisory Council(
DPA), one of the country's high state institution, was
interrogated by the police for 10 hours on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, former Minister of Home Affairs Syarwan Hamid is
expected to be questioned too, over his alleged role in the same
incident which sparked by a forcible takeover of the party's
headquarters in July 27, 1996.
</P>
<P>
During the incident, those who claimed to be loyal to Soerjadi
took over the party's office in Central Jakarta which at that time
was occupied by supporters of the legitimate chairperson Megawati
Soekarnoputeri (now Vice President) activists.
</P>
<P>
A government-back, controversial party congress in early 1996
appointed Soerjadi as PDI chairman. Megawati's staunch backers,
however did not recognize Soerjadi's leadership and refused to
leave the headquarters, and then the bloodshed happened.
</P>
<P>
The National Commission on Human Right (Komnas HAM) announced
in September 1996 that at least five people died, 149 injured,
while 23 were still missing during the riots.
</P>
<P>
Many believed that elements of the Indonesian Military (TNI)
and the central government officials were involved in the attack,
including former Chief of Sociopolitical Affairs of the TNI, Let.
Gen.Syarwan Hamid who was then minister of home affairs under
Habibie Administration.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Pieter's statement, Spokesman of the police,
Brig. Gen. Dadang Garnida said that his office "is now well-
prepared to summon a number of military officers including several
generals."
</P>
</TEXT>
