<HEADLINE> Peru's Opposition Not to Accept Fujimori's Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Peru's presidential candidate
Alejandro Toledo warned Tuesday that the opposition parties won't
accept any result from the National Organization of Electoral
Processes (NOEP) declaring President Alberto Fujimori the winner.
</P>
<P>
He also indicated the parties won't make concessions on their
democratic rights.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics showed Tuesday that with 90.82 percent of
the ballots counted, Fujimori had won 49.79 percent, compared to
Toledo's 40.39 percent.
</P>
<P>
The parties accused NOEP of manipulating the elections to make
Fujimori the absolute winner.
</P>
<P>
"We'll be stubborn in defense of the transparency of
presidential elections", Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori, 61, who came to power in 1990 and won a re-election
in 1995, denied any fraud at a news conference Monday night,
saying the elections are "clean, free and fair".
</P>
<P>
Toledo also urged the president to meet with the opposition in
order to prevent political crisis which might occur as results of
an increase in recession and poverty, as well as an escape of
foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
"I'm asking you, Mr. President, not to think about your current
leadership, nor only about NOEP results. I'm also asking you not
to polarize and put Peruvians face to face," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
