<HEADLINE> Venezuelan President Arrives in Havana for South Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez
arrived in the Cuban capital of Havana Tuesday night for the South
Summit, the first and largest gathering of heads of state and
government since the establishment of the Group of 77 (G-77) in
June 1964.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the Havana airport, Chavez was greeted by
Jose Ramon Fernandez Alvarez, vice chairman of the Cuban Council
of Ministers.
</P>
<P>
Chavez is among some 60 heads of state or government in Havana
to attend the opening ceremony of the Summit on Wednesday morning,
along with scores of foreign ministers and other senior officials.
</P>
<P>
A total of 122 member countries, 34 non-member countries and 35
international organizations have sent delegations here.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation, headed by Vice Premier Li Lanqing,
arrived in Havana Tuesday afternoon. China has for some time had
close ties with G-77. Cuban Foreign Minister Felipe Peraz Roque,
at a press conference Monday, spoke highly of China's support for
the 133-member group.
</P>
<P>
Although the group, founded by 77 developing countries on June
15, 1964 in Geneva, has seen its membership grow to 133 countries,
the original name was retained because of its historic
significance.
</P>
<P>
As the largest grouping in the South, G-77 provides the means
for the developing world to articulate and promote its collective
economic interests, enhance its joint negotiating capacity on
major international economic issues, and promote economic and
technical cooperation among developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
