<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Myanmar Falls Sharply in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar absorbed a total of 49.
553 million U.S. dollars of foreign investment in 1999, 79.94
percent less than the 247 million dollars drawn in 1998, according
to the latest figures issued by the country's Central Statistical
Organization.
</P>
<P>
These investment came from eight countries and regions with
Thailand injecting in 16.5 million dollars, Britain 15 million
dollars, Japan 5.095 million dollars, India 4.5 million dollars,
Singapore 3.261 million dollars, China's Hong Kong 2.5 million
dollars, Indonesia 1.377 million dollars and South Korea 1.32
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The investments covered four sectors of mining, manufacturing,
hotels and tourism, and fishery.
</P>
<P>
The sharp drop of foreign investment is attributed mainly to
the impact of the Asian financial crisis which, the Myanmar
authorities admitted, has brought about a reduction of 70 percent
of direct investment from member countries of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, since Myanmar opened to
foreign investment in late 1988, the country had drawn from 24
countries and regions a total of 7.1 billion dollars of the
investment as of the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Leading foreign investors lined up as Singapore, Britain,
Thailand, Malaysia and France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
