<HEADLINE> OPEC to Review Effects of Oil Output Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan Energy Minister Ali
Rodriguez said on Tuesday that the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) will review the effects of the oil
output increase decided by the organization in March.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC ministers will hold an extraordinary meeting on June
21 in Vienna "to make a balance of the decisions taken in relation
to production, and the market will be analyzed to know its
performance," said Rodriguez in a communique of the Venezuelan
Ministry of Energy.
</P>
<P>
OPEC, which dominates 42 percent of the world oil market,
decided last month to increase their output by an estimated 1.4
million barrels per day to stabilize the oil prices that had risen
to a nine-year high of more than 30 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
This organization, consisting of eleven members, and of which
Venezuela is the third largest producer, cut its output in 1998 to
raise prices which at the beginning of 1999 sank to their lowest
levels in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez said this consecutive lows in oil prices over past
weeks on the world market are due to the coming summer season and
the added offer of oil in the world market.
</P>
<P>
According to official reports, OPEC's oil price has fallen by
seven dollars per barrel since the organization decided to
increase its output.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela's oil was selling last week at 24.32 dollars per
barrel, 75 cents lower than its last week price, according to the
Minister of Energy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
