<HEADLINE> Guatemalan Congress Rejects Access of U.S. Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Guatemalan Congress Tuesday
rejected the entry of U.S. troops into Guatemala to help control
drug traffic and forest fires in the north, said news reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
With the rejection of the opposition parties, especially the
Avanzada Nacional Party (PAN), the ruling Guatemalan Republican
Front (GRF), which holds 63 of the 113 seats in Congress, failed
to obtain 14 more votes needed to pass a law that would allow U.S.
soldiers to enter the country.
</P>
<P>
PAN, which was in power from 1996 to 2000, dismissed the U.S.
military presence as a violation of Guatemala's national
sovereignty, and an indication of ineptitude by the country's
security forces and armies in fighting drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Under the initiative, presented to Congress by President
Alfonso Portillo in March, U.S. cooperation would be part of the
"Maya-Jaguar" narcotics control plan to intercept dealers in the
air, land and water.
</P>
<P>
Portillo asked Guatemalans to show appreciation rather than
criticism of the U.S. military presence, saying that next month he
would personally thank the chief of the U.S. South Command General
Charles Wilhelm for the help they have given his country in
controlling the nearly 180 fires in the northern Peten Forest.
</P>
</TEXT>
