<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Try and Salvage Mideast Peace Negotiations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton,
anxious to secure peace in the Mideast to enhance his eight-year
term at the White House, said Tuesday he would do what he could to
salvage stalled peace negotiations between Israeli-Palestinian and
Israeli-Syrian fronts.
</P>
<P>
"We will do what we can to help," he said on the White House's
south lawn with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak by his side.
</P>
<P>
"There's a lot of hope for rapid movement on the Palestinian
front," he told reporters, adding that the next few weeks would be
critical for progress.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
before her meeting with Barak that the United States hoped the
Israeli-Palestinian talks might move faster.
</P>
<P>
"This is an issue that needs to be done as soon as possible,"
she said, referring to Israel's further pull-out of the West Bank
in June.
</P>
<P>
Hasan Abdel Rahman, the PLO's representative in Washington,
said, however, that there were still "no results" regarding
current negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians at
Bolling Air Force Base near Washington. "Let's hope that will
change," he added.
</P>
<P>
Rahman said the Palestinians wanted Clinton to make clear to
Barak, who was summoned by Clinton to Washington for hasty talks
on the stalled negotiations, that the Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations must be concluded successfully by September 13, a
deadline set by the United States, Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
As for Israel's negotiations with Syria, which broke down in
mid-January because of a dispute over the Israeli withdrawal from
the Golan Heights, Clinton would not rule that those prospects
were dead.
</P>
<P>
"There are still differences," he said. "What we've got to do
is to figure out where we go from here."
</P>
<P>
The difference on the withdrawal was in how much land Israel
would cede in the Golan Heights. Israel agrees to turn over
virtually almost all the territory of the strategic plateau
captured in the 1967 six-day war, except the strip along the
northeast edge of the Sea of Galilee, so it would have full
control of precious water resources. But Syria insists that Israel
must relinquish all the territory extending to the shore of the
lake before the two countries discuss normalization. No compromise
is in sight.
</P>
<P>
Barak said he had "a variety of ideas" to take up with Clinton
about how "to give new momentum and energy to the Palestinian
track" in order to meet the September 13 deadline.
</P>
<P>
Before his meeting with Clinton, Barak has met with U.S.
Mideast envoy Dennis Ross, Albright and National Security Adviser
Sandy Berger.
</P>
<P>
Albright praised Barak at a news conference for planning to
pull Israeli troops out of southern Lebanon in July, pledging that
the United States stands behind Barak's move on that front.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
