<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiangers Bury Dead Under Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 12 (Xinhua) -- People in east China's Zhejiang
Province have decided to do without the fanfare of traditional
Chinese burials and instead deposit the ashes of their dear
departed under trees.
</P>
<P>
At Anxian Cemetery Tuesday, Zhao Ziyan, a worker from the
Hangzhou Mold Factory, planted his mother's ashes under a southern
magnolia, becoming the first citizen in the province to
participate in the region's reform of burial practices.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that it doesn't violate custom and "saves a lot
of money."
</P>
<P>
His wife, Song Shuping, added, "Whenever we see the tree
growing, we see the continuing of the life of our dead relatives."
Both say they want to be buried under trees.
</P>
<P>
Too many tombs have popped up in Zhejiang cemeteries in recent
years, prompting the provincial government to take action to stop
the overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
Vice-governor Zhang Mengjin said that the province's cremation
rate has exceeded 70 percent, adding that more and more people are
expected to take advantage of the space-saving, cost-effective
burial alternative.
</P>
<P>
"This can save land, and beautify the environment," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Local citizens will be charged about 600 yuan (about 72.28 U.S.
dollars) per tree per burial. Cemetery workers are responsible for
watering and pruning the trees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Foresees Larger Sales of Textile Machinery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- China's home-made textile
machinery will be more popular this year, with sales climbing to
12 billion yuan (145 million U.S.dollars) and exports hitting 200
million U.S. dollars, according to "China Materials News."
</P>
<P>
Gao Tong, vice chairman of China Textile Industry Association,
expected the sales of textile machinery to resume its peak in the
1993-94 period, basing his forecast on orders received by
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
China's textile industry, which has been declining in recent
years, is upgrading its technology.
</P>
<P>
The exports of Chinese textile machinery is also undergoing
rapid growth with an estimated increase of 20 percent thanks to
the state's taxation policies and improved production.
</P>
<P>
Gao called for greater attention of the government to
development of new products as well as more favorable taxation
policies in view of the sustained growth of the textile machinery
industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
