<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Galatasaray: We Want to Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Galatasaray said they have no
plans to boycott next week's UEFA Cup semi-final tie against Leeds,
even if their fans are banned from the second-leg clash.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish side will discover on Wednesday whether Leeds can
guarantee the safety of Turkish fans travelling to Elland Road,
following the murder of two English fans in Istanbul last week.
</P>
<P>
Five Turkish youths have since been held in connection with the
murders.
</P>
<P>
Galatasaray president Faruk Suren dismissed suggestions his
club were seeking to qualify for the final without kicking a ball.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on BBC Radio 5 Live, Suren said: "While we think it is
unfair that this matter carries on and that Turkish supporters
should not be allowed to travel, we will come and play without our
supporters if that is what Uefa decide.
</P>
<P>
"It is within their rules to forbid them to come if they so
wish. All I would ask is that Uefa and Leeds will be able to
guarantee the security of the team before, during and after the
match."
</P>
<P>
Suren said the apparent insensitivity of the Galatasaray
players not to wear black armbands in last Thursday's match had
stemmed from a UEFA ruling and not from him.
</P>
<P>
"It is not true that we are seeking to make the final without
kicking another ball. To play on that and try and put the blame on
Galatasaray is not fair. Let Turkish justice take care of the
matter and I hope they will hand out the justified sentences to
those who are guilty," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
