<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ferguson Joins EU Players Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- English premier league soccer club
Manchester United manager Alex Ferguson is joining the debate
about limiting the number of foreign players in the English
leagues.
</P>
<P>
He will be heading to the European Parliament in Strasbourg on
Wednesday, together with Michel Platini and Gerhard Aigner of UEFA
for talks along with FIFA and European Union officials.
</P>
<P>
There are concerns that national teams, including England,
cannot compete well at international level because of a lack of
homegrown talent due to the amount of foreign players in the
leagues.
</P>
<P>
UEFA believe up to six players who are eligible for the club's
national squad should be in a team.
</P>
<P>
The move would affect a number of top continental clubs,
including Chelsea, who recently fielded a non-English team in two
crucial games.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman said: "There will be an on-going discussion into
different issues regarding the Bosman ruling and foreign players
in the game. Sir Alex Ferguson, Michel Platini and Gerhard Aigner
will be attending along with representatives from FIFA and the EU.
"
</P>
<P>
The footballing hierarchies want to debate a number of issues
including a limit on the number of foreign players in EU countries
and the Bosman ruling.
</P>
<P>
UEFA said there will be no final decision on the day but want
change quickly.
</P>
<P>
It would be designed to counter the trend of rich European
clubs lining up mostly foreign players.
</P>
<P>
In a 1995 ruling, the EU's highest court backed Belgian player
Jean-Marc Bosman in a labour contract dispute, effectively ending
limits on EU foreigners and bringing free agency to European
leagues.
</P>
<P>
But UEFA said the Bosman decision was made for economic reasons
and football should be exempt.
</P>
<P>
Another negative aspect of the Bosman ruling has been the
decline in youth training, since small clubs no longer can sell
prodigies at high prices to rich clubs when youngsters are out of
contract. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campbell: Red Tape Ruin Spurs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- English premier league soccer club
Tottenham Hotspur captain Sol Campbell has hit out at the club's
hierarchy for a lack of silverware.
</P>
<P>
Campbell insists manager George Graham is not to blame for
Tottenham's absence of trophies and instead points the finger at
the White Hart Lane hierarchy for holding back the club.
</P>
<P>
During Graham's first season Spurs won the Worthington Cup but
this season the team has been poor in the league and the cup
competitions.
</P>
<P>
And many Spurs fans have turned on Graham for his failure to
sign any proven international-class players.
</P>
<P>
Campbell said: "It's pretty much out of the manager's hands.
</P>
<P>
"The managerial system is split. It's in the hands of different
people and different departments. There's a lot of red tape. I
don't know if it's finances or certain people's attitudes that are
holding us back. I just hope the right people wake up and realize,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
The England defender has been linked with a move to Manchester
United, but is still willing to negotiate an extension to his
contract, which is due to end in the summer of 2001.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to talk again at the end of the season. I've said
that from day one and kept my side of the bargain," said Campbell.
</P>
<P>
"I want this club to do well but there's a gap between us and
the top sides. We need to close it not let it open up further. It'
s within the club's capabilities but attitudes must change," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
