<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Tightens Measures to Tackle Water Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government Wednesday
announced new measures to save water as the tiny island is faced
with a severe water shortage problem due to dry weather.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Cyprus News Agency, those measures
include redistribution of water resources in cities and possible
import of water from Greece, said Minister of Agriculture, Natural
Resources and Environment Costas Themistocleous after a cabinet
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Rainfall in Cyprus this year is about 60 percent of the normal
precipitation and the island's reservoirs hold 42 million cubic
metres of water, compared to 62 million the year before, said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
"This is the sixth driest year of this century and unfortunately
we have to continue imposing restrictions in the water supply for
drinking as well as for agriculture," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's water resources available can cover only
75 percent of household and industrial water needs, and agriculture
needs will only be met by about 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Total water supplies on the island are about 57 million cubic
metres but the total needs are about 138 million cubic metres, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said Nicosia, Limassol and Larnaca, the three largest cities
in Cyprus, will get water in proportion to their population.
</P>
<P>
Special water saving equipment will be installed in government-
run buildings such as schools, offices and army camps.
</P>
<P>
Water supply cuts have been in force for the past few years in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government is in touch with Greece to discuss the
possibility of importing water and is also examining other options
in order to meet the country's water needs in the summer months, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Opens First Arabic Ministerial Website </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Ministry of Industry and
Trade on Wednesday launched the Arabic-language version of its
Internet site, the first of its kind for an Israeli ministry.
</P>
<P>
The site, http://www.israel-industry-trade.gov.il/arabic, is to
provide information in Arabic about projects, training programs
under the authority of the ministry, and industrial regulations in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The site could serve as a hi-tech aid for potential investors
and businessmen who speak Arabic.
</P>
<P>
It is viewed as a mini-breakthrough for the equality between
Jews and Arabs in Israeli society, at least in the cyberspace. The
minister Ran Cohen, a dovish political figure of the left-wing
Meretz party, reportedly played a role behind the decision.
</P>
<P>
Although Arabic is one of the two official languages in Israel
and used by nearly one-fifth of its population, it was ignored by
the majority Jews for a long time.
</P>
<P>
For example, Israeli airports, seaports, border crossings and
railway stations were not obligated to have Arabic signs until
recently.
</P>
<P>
Under pressure from Arab groups which threatened to appeal to
Israel's Supreme Court, the Airports Authority agreed last month
that signs in Arabic would be installed at all Ben-Gurion
International Airport terminals and the issue would be studied for
implementation at the country's airfields.
</P>
<P>
Over one million Israeli Arab citizens live in self-contained
towns and villages in Israel, with a growing sense of bitterness
and frustration toward the Jews-dominated society.
</P>
<P>
A recent poll conducted by Givat Haviva's Institute for Peace
Research found that Israeli Arabs are beginning to see themselves
more as Palestinians living in Israel than as a full-fledged
Israeli citizen.
</P>
<P>
Local Arab communities also blamed the government for not paying
enough attention to their social and economic development. Their
leaders have organized several demonstrations since February to
force the government to allocate more funds for their communities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Jiang's Speech at Welcoming Dinner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The following is the full text
of the speech made by Chinese President Jiang Zemin at the
welcoming dinner hosted by Israeli President Ezer Weizman here
Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
It is a great honor for me to visit your beautiful country as
the new century and the new millennium are dawning upon human
civilization. May I begin by thanking you, Mr. President and Mrs.
Weizman, on behalf of my wife and my colleagues and in my own name,
for hosting this grand welcoming dinner for us and for your kind
remarks. I also wish to take this opportunity to extend my cordial
greetings and good wishes to the friendly people of Israel and to
pay high tribute to the Jewish nation that has produced such giants
as Karl Marx and Albert Einstein.
</P>
<P>
"Take history as a mirror, and one knows why dynasties changed."
Both the Chinese and Jewish nations have a long history and a
splendid culture and both have made outstanding contributions to
the progress of human civilization. And both had misfortunes in the
past. The long evolution our two nations have gone through and the
unyielding struggles we have waged amidst hardships and miseries
not only attest to our national identity, i.e. persistence in self-
improvement, but also represent the trend of the times - the human
society is bound to overcome all difficulties and obstacles and
press ahead towards a bright future. Eventually, backwardness,
ignorance and evils in all forms will be conquered and progress,
science and justice will prevail. This is an irresistible law of
history.
</P>
<P>
Mankind has created hitherto unknown material and spiritual
wealth in the 20th century, but has also been subjected to the
scourge of wars and the threat of war. In the Middle East, ethnic
conflicts, territorial disputes and endless flames of war have over
the years taken countless lives and displaced numerous people. That
has severely dampened the economic and social development of the
region and affected world peace and stability. At the time when the
Old Testament was written over 2,000 years ago on this fertile
land, our forefathers in China advanced the doctrine that "harmony
is the best option." Many stories of "burying hatchet" have been
handed down in the Chinese history. Having gone through the long
years, people have come to understand more than ever before how
important this doctrine is and how precious peace can be.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Middle East is at a historic turning point.
Peace, stability and development have become a strong and common
aspiration of all the peoples in the region. Due to reasons of
history and the realities, there is no easy solution to the Middle
East question which involves complicated contradictions.
Nevertheless, to settle the question at an early date is the
unshirkable historical responsibility of the people of all
countries in the region as well as all the peace-loving and
progressive people in the world. The settlement lies in peaceful
negotiations rather than force, in cooperation rather than
confrontation, and in mutual understanding rather than mutual
exclusion. This has increasingly become a consensus drawn from past
experience and lessons. Now thanks to the joint efforts of all the
parties concerned, much progress has been made in the Middle East
peace process. The relevant U.N. resolutions and the "land-for-
peace" principle have become the basis for negotiations among the
parties. It is gratifying and encouraging to note that leaders of
the Middle East countries, with the vision and courage of
statesmen, in a historical perspective and bearing in mind the
greater interests of peace and development, are working hard for an
early settlement of the Middle East question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Countries Pay for Rich Countries' Mistakes: G-77 Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- President of the Group of 77 (G-
77), Nigerian leader Olusegun Obasanjo said on Wednesday here
that poor countries pay for the mistakes of the rich world,
despite the fact that "we are all in the same boat."
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo, who opened the South Summit, said that the developing
world is stranded because the developed countries are not
enforcing measures that guarantee poor nation's access to
technology.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries' heavy foreign debt is endangering their
future, and that South-South cooperation agreements up to now are
only "dead letter", he said.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, changes that will make the world a fairest
place, should be based upon principles like the reform of
financial institutions, thus a new architecture should be erected,
besides a reduction or even an elimination of foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
As regards to South-South cooperation, he set the Economic
Organization for Western African Countries (ECOWAS) as an example.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
