<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania to Draw up Strategy for Prevention of Natural, Ecological Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Romania's Supreme Defense
Council(CSAT) decided at its Wednesday's meeting that the
executive would present, by the end of May, a medium and long-term
strategy concerning the prevention of the negative effects of
natural and ecological disasters.
</P>
<P>
CSAT, the country's highest institution in charge of issues of
national security, held on Wednesday an emergency meeting to
discuss the risks posed to national security by recent floods and
ecological accidents. A series of measures are to be taken to
fight the effects of the mentioned disasters.
</P>
<P>
According to Romanian President Emil Constantinescu who
presided the meeting, the authorities would supply material,
financial help and other first necessity products for all the
afflicted persons in the recent floods and give temporary shelter
to those whose houses were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Immediate measures will be taken to protect the localities and
the public property against new flash floods, the head of the
state said, adding that the Executive is going to take necessary
steps for the evaluation, in two weeks, of the needs of materials
for repair and the offering of new lodgings for the affected
families,the repairing of the infrastructure and of the public
utilities affected.
</P>
<P>
The heavy rainfall and the rapid melting of snow in the first
few days of April caused floods in most regions of the country,
with the center, the northwest and the southwest of Romania being
the most affected. The damage caused is considered as the heaviest
in the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures released on Wednesday, as many as
9,502 homes were inundated in 465 towns and villages between April
4-11. More than 87,950 hectares of farmland were covered by waters;
floods damaged 575 bridges, 65 social and economic units,and 65
hydrotechnical constructions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
