<HEADLINE> Non-Aligned Countries Call for Development System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The President of the Non-Aligned
Movement Countries Organization, South African leader Thabo Mbeki,
made a call on Wednesday at Havana, for a world development system
centered on man.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 122 delegations present at the first South
Summit, which started on Monday and will be over on April 14,
Mbeki said that such a system must be part of world solidarity,
and "a sense of world citizenship which must transcend
cosmopolitanism."
</P>
<P>
He reminded that the chief of the International Monetary Fund (
IMF), Michel Camdessus, favored this point of view during a recent
participation in Washington, where he pledged for a global
solidarity.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki quoted Camdessus as saying that traditional power
structures and interests of rich countries have to be challenged
in order to achieve this goal.
</P>
<P>
The Non-Aligned Movement leader set as an example the lack of
this world citizenship, the case of Mozambique, where not so long
ago violent floods ravaged the country.
</P>
<P>
Western countries, he said, went to help Mozambique, but did
not do what was really needed for a country within such
circumstances, that is eliminating its foreign debt. "Having done
so would have been against their national policies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Following, he highlighted the coincidences of criteria between
the G-77 and the Non-Aligned Movement, whose main objectives are
getting closer, in search of a further interaction and
concentration of positions.
</P>
<P>
Together we have to look for the elimination of poverty and the
raising of quality of life level in our countries, as well as the
defense of national identities and community cohesion, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki thanked the G-77 and China for having given him the
possibility to speak at the forum, and recognized Cuba's people
and government for the effective organization of the Summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
