<HEADLINE> Castro Supports South-South Oil Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"There should be a solution that benefits all of us," the
Cuban leader said while speaking to South Summit's plenary
meeting on Wednesday in Havana.
</P>
<P>
Castro said that as an expression of the South-South
cooperation, a different prices oil system could become a real
instrument for the Third World development.
</P>
<P>
"Third World solidarity within itself cannot continue allowing
its countries to pay for the oil, same prices rich countries pay,
for they even waste it, whereas poor countries barely use it," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Castro said that the San Jose Agreement created 20 years ago by
Mexico and Venezuela for oil exports to Central America and the
Caribbean in preferential conditions is a good precedent of what
developing countries can do.
</P>
<P>
He highlighted the need to establish a different price system
that turns into a concrete reality South-South cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that no developing country should pay over 20 dollars
per oil barrel, and some not even 10 dollars, while industrialized
countries would more easily pay for the 30 dollars, oil price
reached during the last months.
</P>
