<HEADLINE> Canada Allocates Millions of Dollars to Improve Rail System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The federal government of Canada
announced an allocation of 401.9 million Canadian dollars (about
277.3 million U.S. dollars) Wednesday to improve the country's
rail system.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Transport Minister David Collenett said the government
will give Via Rail the money over the next five years to buy new
rail cars, modernize signal systems and fix up the line between
Quebec City and Windsor in southern Ontario.
</P>
<P>
The new money will also boost Via's ability to clean up
stations and treat waste.
</P>
<P>
"We are putting an end to the deterioration of Canada's
passenger rail system," the minister said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
The allocation came as Via was reported to lose a yearly 190
million Canadian dollars (about 131 million U.S. dollars) while
receiving 170 million (about 117 million U.S. dollars) in public
money in management to keep the trains running.
</P>
<P>
Collenette said subsidies are at the core of passenger rail
everywhere else in the world.
</P>
<P>
Via is a Crown corporation of the country that serves 3.8
million passengers and 450 communities. 
