<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0350 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Sees U.S. Economy Slowing Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The IMF, in its twice-yearly World Economic Outlook, said the U.
S. economy would likely ease to a "soft landing." But it cautioned
there was no evidence that growth, boosted by rising stock prices,
would slow on its own.
</P>
<P>
An alternative -- less likely -- scenario assumed a pickup in
global growth and inflation, followed by higher interest rates, a
25 percent correction in highly valued U.S. equity prices and a 20
percent slump in the dollar in response to a reversal of capital
flows, the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
This would virtually bring U.S. growth to a halt and knock
almost a full percentage point off economic growth in the world
outlook next year, it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The IMF recommended that the U.S. Federal Reserve probably need
to continue to move progressively but prudently to a tighter
monetary stance.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, speaking at a press conference Wednesday, IMF chief
economist Michael Mussa said the U.S. economy, the largest in the
world, will grow more strongly than expected in coming months,
forcing the Federal Reserve to move so aggressively to increase
interest rates that it could push the United States into a mild
recession starting in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Mussa said the IMF believes the most likely outcome is not a "
hard landing" and recession in the United States but a "soft
landing" in which the Federal Reserve is successful in slowing the
economy to a more sustainable pace that keeps inflation under
control.
</P>
<P>
"The stock market, in addition to a number of other indicators,
is suggesting growing imbalances in the U.S. economy that make it
appropriate for monetary policy here to move to a somewhat tighter
stance," Mussa said.
</P>
<P>
Since last June, the U.S. Federal Reserve has raised its funds
overnight bank lending rate five times. It has bumped up the rate
by a quarter-percentage point each time to try to slow down demand
to a point where it no longer exceeds the economy's potential to
produce -- so far with little apparent success.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve is expected to continue raising rates at
its next two or three meetings, but few in financial markets think
it will move to a more aggressive policy of half-point rate rises -
- a strategy that would be difficult to defend absent a
significant rise in still-dormant consumer price inflation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
