<HEADLINE> Castro Proposes to Substitute IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Cuban President Fidel Castro
Wednesday proposed the developing countries to unite and pledge
together for the International Monetary Fund (IMF) dissolution and
the establishment of a new financial order based upon democracy
and equity.
</P>
<P>
For the Third World it is important to make this sinister
organization and the philosophy it represents disappear, said the
Cuban leader.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he proposed the creation of a regulatory organ for
international finances to work under a democratic basis, without
any sort of veto power by anyone.
</P>
<P>
While addressing his words during the opening of the Group of
77 South Summit, Castro denounced the United States for having
veto power on IMF decisions, and accused this organization for
having clumsily managed the last Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
If Cuba has advanced in education, health and other social
sectors, it is because it is not part of the IMF and has not had
to submit to its rulings, he said.
</P>
<P>
In relation to the IMF, Castro said that it is time for the
Third World to demand de destruction of this organism which does
not offer a world economic stability.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, because it works not to give preventive funds for
debtors and this way prevent them to have liquidity problems, but
to protect and rescue creditors, said the Cuban president.
</P>
