<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Countries' Debt Problem Is Political Issue, Castro Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the South Summit of the
Group of 77 (G-77), Castro, who wears a suit to represent the host
country, said "Today, it is clear than ever that the debt is not
an economic but a political issue, therefore, it demands a
political solution."
</P>
<P>
"It is impossible to continue overlooking the fact that the
solution to this problem must basically come from those with
resources and power, that is, the wealthy countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The underdeveloped nations external debt is amazing not only
because it is terrible but also due to its outrageous mechanism of
subjugation and exploitation and the absurd formula offered by the
developed countries to cope with it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Debt issue is one of the major concerns for the leaders from
developing countries who are here to attend the South Summit, the
largest gathering of heads of state and government since the G-77
founding in 1964.
</P>
<P>
That debt already exceeds 2.5 trillion U.S. dollars and in the
present decade it has been increasing more dangerously than in the
1970s. A large part of that new debt can easily change hands in
the secondary markets; it is more dispersed now and more difficult
to reschedule.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The debt continues to feed on itself in a vicious
circle where money is borrowed to pay its interests."
</P>
<P>
"The so-called Heavily Indebted Poor Countries Debt Reduction
Initiative exhibits a long name but poor results," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It can only be described as a ridiculous attempt at
alleviating 8.3 percent of the South countries total debt; but
almost four years after its implementation only four countries
among the poorest 33 have reached the complicated process simply
to condone the negligible figure of 2.7 billion U.S. dollars,
which is 33 percent of what the United States spends on cosmetics
every year," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Today, the external debt is one of the greatest obstacles to
development and a bomb ready to blow up the foundations of the
world economy at any time during an economic crisis," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
