<HEADLINE> Colombia Arrests 49 Drug Lords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Colombian police head General
Rosso Jose Serrano Cadena, said Wednesday that in the past hours
the number of captured in "Milenio dos" operation has gone up to
49.
</P>
<P>
Colombia's National Police and General Attorney with support
from U.S. Antidrug Agency(DEA), took apart at dawn Wednesday the
largest drug cartel of heroin traffic in the world and initially
held 46 people, among them four heads of the organization.
</P>
<P>
The operation took place by way of 65 searches in Bogota,
Medellin, Cali, Cucuta, Popayan, Buenaventura and three
municipalities of Cauca department.
</P>
<P>
Among those held are Nicolas Alberto de San Cayetano Urquijo
Gaviria, cousin of deceased Medellin cartel leader, Pablo Escobar,
who perished in a confrontation with police in 1993.
</P>
<P>
General Rosso Jose Serrano, and DEA director in Colombia, Leo
Arregwi, traveled to Cali, capital of Valle del Cauca department,
to present those held before the press.
</P>
<P>
Police action, as well as that of the Attorney, and DEA,
counted with support of planes and helicopters provided with
special equipment.
</P>
<P>
Urquijo Gaviria, captured in Medellin, is seen as the most
important head of this organization, taken apart Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Another three "high rank" heads of this heroin cartel fell
into police hands in Bogota.
</P>
<P>
Five other people implied in this network are being looked for
by Colombian police, according to official spokespersons, who
abstained from providing names. 
</P>
