<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Leader Fails to Promise to Speed Up Plan Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I am supportive of the Colombian aid package. I feel very
strongly that it will be completed in May or early June," Lott
told reporters after meeting with Pastrana in the Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
Lott said he was eager to include the aid as part of the normal
appropriations process,hopefully within the next three months, but
not as emergency legislation.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana started his two-day visit to the United States on
Tuesday in order to persuade the Senate to approve the
administration's Plan Colombia worth 1.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton proposed the emergency aid package for
Colombia earlier this year to help Colombians build security, halt
the production of illegal drugs and the proposal easily sailed
through the House last month but faces a delay in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on
Wednesday, Pastrana said that his country will eradicate half of
crops of cocaine or poppy in his country in five years.
</P>
<P>
"I think that if we really want to avoid the growing of these
type of crops or cocaine or poppy in Colombia, we need the money
because we need to invest, not only in the eradication program,
but also investing in the alternative development programs,"
Pastrana said.
</P>
<P>
"That's why you would think that not only would the resources
for promoting alternative development but also the resources to
support the police and the army in the fight against drugs will be
very important for us," he added.
</P>
<P>
Albright renewed the administration's call for rapid action by
the Senate to approve the plan.
</P>
<P>
"Four-fifths of the cocaine entering our country either comes
from Colombia or is transported through it. Most of Colombia's
heroin production also ends up here. Throughout the Americas,
drug-related activities fuel crime and corruption, aggravates
social problems and retard economic progress," she added.
</P>
<P>
Albright also praised the plan by Pastrana. "Only Colombians
can devise a solution for Colombia's ills, and President Pastrana
has put forward a bold plan for doing just that."
</P>
<P>
"It's urgent that we support him not with the promise of help,
but with its reality; not eventually, but now," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Senate indefinitely postpones votes scheduled by the Senate
Appropriations Committee on a spending package that includes Plan
Colombia. The House has approved the aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
