<HEADLINE> Uganda's Ruling Party to Continue With Its Policies After Referendum: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
said here Wednesday that the National Resistance Movement (NRM),
the ruling party of the country, would continue with its policies
if it wins in the forthcoming referendum.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when addressing a public rally on his
second referendum campaign day in Nakasongola District, according
to a press release from the President's Office.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said that the people of Uganda can continue building
on the gains they have made since the advent of the NRM system if
they vote for the ruling party in the referendum scheduled for
the coming June.
</P>
<P>
The future plans by the NRM include modernization of
agriculture, attracting more foreign investment and constructing
more secondary schools to absorb the products of the Universal
Primary Education program launched in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
It is the NRM that brought together people of different groups
and brought political stability and economic development to the
country.
</P>
<P>
Under Uganda's 1995 Constitution, a referendum is to be held in
June to decide on the country's future political system. The
ruling party is widely believed to come out the winner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
