<HEADLINE> Algerian President Demands Equity in Globalized World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The President of Algeria,
Abdelaziz Bouteflika, said on Wednesday that the development
problem has changed with the advance of globalization in world
economy, but this process has to take into account the interests
of every state.
</P>
<P>
Bouteflika, who presides the African Unity Organization (AUO),
is participating in the general debate of the South Summit taking
place in Havana.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian leader said that during the last years an
important transformation in international relations has taken
place and the economic order of today brings with it new threats
to the sovereignty of states.
</P>
<P>
He said that market forces have to be regulated in order not
to provoke further unbalance and destruction in Third World
countries.
</P>
<P>
Bouteflika said that in Africa, foreign capital investments are
ridiculous and one of its causes, he said, is that local markets
have shrunk due to prevailing inequality.
</P>
<P>
Finally, he asked an alleviation in the foreign debt load
affecting the Third World, saying that difficult conditions
affecting many peoples in Sub-Saharan Africa have to be taken into
account.  
</P>
</TEXT>
