<HEADLINE> South Africa to Share Potential with Developing World: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- With its economic potential, one
of the strongest in Africa, South Africa expects to make a notable
contribution to South-South cooperation in the southern part of
the continent, said here the Presidency Minister, Essop Pahad.
</P>
<P>
In declarations to the press at the South Summit at this
capital, Pahad said that these expectations will concentrate in a
Free Trade Zone (FTZ) in Southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
This zone will be completed during the next months as part of
one of the most important issue of the summit of the Group of 77 (
G-77): South-South cooperation.
</P>
<P>
For Pahad, the road to this kind of exchange has to determine
first what nations have the highest development levels, like
Argentina or India who are actually investing in other nations of
the South.
</P>
<P>
Regarding to his country, Essop Pahad said that it is
developing a series of projects, with particular attention to the
mining sector, but at the same time is stimulating internal
business to invest in other nations of the South.
</P>
<P>
He said that this summit, instead of adding more new ideas on
globalization and relations with the North, should pay more
attention to the application of the dispositions already agreed
upon during the past Non-Aligned Movement countries summit at
Durban, in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, he said that another important aspiration
that his country shares with what has already been expressed by
Cuba, is the creation of a common front of developing countries,
he said.
</P>
<P>
This is something that would "allow us to face immense problems
we have as developing countries and in our relations with the
North."  
</P>
</TEXT>
