<DOCNO> XIE20000412.0366 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A0004030 America's West Coast Most Wired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A greater percentage of
people have access to the Internet on the West Coast than anywhere
else in the United States, according to survey results released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Four of the top five local markets with the largest Internet
penetration for the month of February were on the West Coast,
showed the results announced by Nielsen/NetRatings, an Internet
measurement service. The top five are San Francisco, Seattle,
Portland, San Diego and Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
As a comparison, 61 percent of the people in San Francisco had
access to the Internet. Los Angeles ranked tenth with 43.9 percent
penetration, and the last of the 20 cities surveyed, Cleveland,
had a penetration of 36.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Markets that are well known technology centers lead the pack
in terms of Web penetration," NetRatings said. "The various '
Alleys' and 'Valleys' across the U.S. appear to have the largest
concentration of early Internet adopters."
</P>
<P>
The top five Internet penetration markets are also ranked in
the top ten local television markets. "Knowing where Web
penetration is high sheds light on areas likely to lead the move
to TV-Internet convergence, and could help technology and media
companies, who are setting their sights on new multimedia content
services, understand the markets that could provide them the
largest initial opportunities," said Nielsen/NetRating.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, the market with the largest unique
Internet audience (individual users counted only once) during
February was New York (4.3 million), followed by Los Angeles (3.6
million), San Francisco-Oakland-San Jose (2.2 million), and
Chicago (2.1 million).
</P>
<P>
San Diego, California, had the highest average time spent
online per person for February. Users in the city spent an average
of more than 11 hours online during the month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
