<HEADLINE> Namibian Presidents Calls for Ending Armed Conflicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam Nujoma
exhorted on Wednesday in a statement pronounced at the South
Summit, to put an end to every armed conflict in Third World
countries.
</P>
<P>
He also made a call to the countries of the Group of 77 (G-77)
to face together the globalization challenges since only this way,
a true solidarity, he said, "we will be able to incorporate
ourselves to a globalized economy."
</P>
<P>
Nujoma said that with the enormous natural resources existing
in the countries of the South, it is possible to achieve economic
development, but "the existence of an unfair international order
is an obstacle to reach it," he said.
</P>
<P>
He refuted those who claim that no democratic government has to
fear globalization, arguing that if the world order is neither
democratic nor just, then there are reasons to fight for
substantial changes.
</P>
<P>
With globalization, the President of Namibia said, having the
challenge to reach a just economic order, it is important to
remain united and in peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
