<HEADLINE> Ending Foreign Debt not Enough: Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique declared on Wednesday
before the 122 delegations present at the South Summit at this
capital, that it is not enough to eliminate foreign debt affecting
the poorest countries future, for they also need further help for
development.
</P>
<P>
Official Development Assistance alone, in combination with
foreign debt elimination will allow us to celebrate the advances
and benefits of globalization, said the President of Mozambique,
Joaquim Chissano.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the southern African nation is one of the 42
heads of state present during the South Summit's meeting, the
first summit since the Group of 77 (G-77) was founded at Geneva,
Switzerland in 1964.
</P>
<P>
The countries of the South, said Chissano, have never benefited
with globalization, for until now they have not been but subject
to the process, always directed by the industrialized world'
nations.
</P>
<P>
We must revert our condition of globalized countries we have
acquired, designing for that, strategies that change such a
situation and have a more active role, according to the interests
of our peoples.
</P>
<P>
According to Chissano, the benefits originated by globalization
more often are going to the North, which is widening the space
between both blocks.
</P>
<P>
He also talked about the challenge that poor nations face
against external forces unleashed by finances and trade
globalization.
</P>
<P>
We still live in an unfair context, little democratic and
unbalanced.
</P>
<P>
The Summit at Havana started last April 10 and will finish next
April 14, when the Action Program and the final Havana Declaration
are to be completed.
</P>
</TEXT>
