<HEADLINE> Middle East Peace Begins in Palestine:Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Arafat also asked the Group of 77 (G-77) to recognize the
independent state his organization expects to create this year.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward the South Summit recognizing our state," said
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is present at the summit along with delegates of 122
countries, which represent the nations of the developing world to
discuss ways to cooperate among themselves, ways to have access to
up-to-date technology and their relations with the advanced North.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the situation in the Middle East, Arafat said that
peace and stability in the region depend on peace of the
territories under his authority, Gaza, the West Bank and East
Jerusalem, held by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, there will be no peace, until the Palestinian
rights to freedom and independence become a reality, as well as
the withdrawal of Israel from the occupied territories, and the
birth of an independent state with East Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the Palestine Liberation Front wished the Havana
Declaration and the Program of Action resulting from the Summit, "
guarantee a fruitful cooperation among nations and set the basis
for an international cooperation based on fair terms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
