<HEADLINE> Romania's 2000 Budget Marks Non-Inflationary Economic Growth: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Romania's budget for 2000 will
mark a re-start of the non-inflationary economic growth and the
country's regaining credibility, the Prime Minister Mugur Isarescu
told parliamentarians at a meeting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Parliament on Wednesday started debating in both
chambers the draft state budget for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting, the prime minister said, in his opening
speech, that the government had proposed, in the draft budget, an
economic growth of 1.3 percent, a drop in the inflation rate by a
half to 27 percent and a budget deficit of 3 percent of the Gross
Domestic Product(GDP).
</P>
<P>
"Romania will have an economic growth and an inflation drop
that stimulates the effectiveness and creates an appropriate
business environment", he said, stressing that the planned
economic growth was based on an increase in the exports and
investments and less on the stimulation of revenues.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Romania's foreign debt, Mugur Isarescu pointed out
that Romania's public debt had not gone up in the past three years
and said that the public debt, at 35 percent of the GDP, is well
beyond the maximum limit of 60 percent stipulated in the
Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
He said that Romania was re-gaining credibility "with proofs,
figures and economic developments that cannot be disputed".
</P>
<P>
The prime minister cautioned that "re-build of credibility
should start from inside the country, through our belief that we
have the capacity to restart the economy".
</P>
<P>
Isarescu said that in the second half of this would be
stabilized, following a sped-up economic growth. According to him,
beginning the year 2001, Romania will have an economic growth of 4-
5 percent per year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
