<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Supports Savings and Investment Bank Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is promoting a savings and
investment bank project for Africa, an effort within the frame of
South-South cooperation initiatives announced these days at Havana,
where the Group of 77 (G-77) meets.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Foreign Minister Bonaya Adhis Godana told the press
that his country is not bearing any individual claim in this event,
for it sees its future closely linked to developing countries
around the world.
</P>
<P>
But as part of this conglomerate, represented at Havana by 122
delegations, the African country considers that it can do a lot,
like participating in the creation of this bank which would be
headquartered in his territory.
</P>
<P>
"We are linked also to the regional solidarity promotion
through the Common Market for the South of Africa and the search
of an world economic authority," said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
"We aspire every organization come together under a single
entity, that gives way to the new and just world order we need,"
added the official.
</P>
<P>
Godana also said it would be important that the countries of G-
77 acquire new compromises, reaffirmation and be conscious of the
need of a real world solidarity in a world where we run the risk
of being totally marginalized, Africa in particular.
</P>
<P>
As for specific preoccupation that his country wanted to
discuss at the Summit, the official referred to the need of
developing countries' products to have access to rich countries'
markets.
</P>
<P>
He also talked about the need of a more democratic United
Nations system, and of international organizations like the World
Trade Organization generating a more just exchange between
developed and developing countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
